<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Opera Focus of China Culture Week in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Opera became the focus of
attention on Wednesday at the `99 Paris China Culture Week here,
when a famous Chinese actress gave a lecture on the 200-year-old
drama which represents one of the best fine arts in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuzheng, the Directress of the Theater of Beijing Opera in
Beijing, gave a simple but clear explanation about the major
esthetic features of Beijing Opera to 500 French listeners at the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organizations
(UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
With a combination of poetry, music, language, dance, painting,
costume, scenery creation and martial art, Beijing Opera is a form
of art which cannot find its exact version in the West, she said.
</P>
<P>
During their performances, the actors and actresses of Beijing
Opera drink, read, recite, sit, fight and dance, and their
characters are represented through different masks featuring
happiness, anger, sadness, amusement and fear, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
She said that compared with Western opera, one of the unique
feature of Beijing Opera is that it does not need many accessories,
because the story and scene are mainly presented through the actions
of actors and actresses.
</P>
<P>
"A table with cups on it and an arm chair are enough to
represent a tea house. A whip in hand is enough to represent a
horse. An oar is enough to represent a boat," she said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that in contrary to the tradition of Western opera
which relies on scenery to present acts, the Beijing Opera relies on
acts to present scenery.
</P>
<P>
"Because of its heavy reliance on acts, Beijing Opera can
overcome the barrier of language, bring about mutual understanding
between actors and audience through actions and gestures, and
become understandable to people from different cultures," she said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Opera is little like Chinese literature and painting,
which also emphasizes subjective feeling and sensation rather than
objective accuracy, which is the case in Western literature and
painting.
</P>
<P>
One retired professor of the Sorbonne University of Paris said
that the Beijing Opera relies more on human efforts than Western
opera.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, he suggested that it no longer bear the
misleading name of "opera," but be called "humane opera" or
simply "Jingxi" in Western languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
