<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Fines Journalist Already in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian journalist, already
in prison for defaming the agriculture minister, was fined
Wednesday 10,000 pounds (2,950 U.S. dollars) by the Alexandria
Criminal Court for libeling the minister's deputy.
</P>
<P>
Youssef Abdel-Rahman, Agriculture Minister Youssef Wali's
deputy, accused Salah Bdeiwi, a reporter with the opposition
Al-Shaab newspaper, of defaming him in several articles in the
Al-Shaab, the mouthpiece of the Islamist opposition Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
Bdeiwi was sentenced last month along with the paper's
editor-in-chief Magdi Hussein and cartoonist Essam Hanafi to two
years in jail for libeling Wali. Each of the two was also fined
20,000 pounds (5,900 dollars).
</P>
<P>
A fourth journalist of Al-Shaab, Adel Hussein, a columnist and
the editor's brother, was acquitted but fined 20,000 pounds for
defaming Wali to a lower degree.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaab accused Wali of destroying the economy for Israel's
sake and termed him a "traitor."
</P>
<P>
Wali signed several agreements with Israel for the supply of
seeds, fertilizers and technology to arrest desertification.
</P>
</TEXT>
