<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger, Haig Urges End of U.S-China Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Secretaries of
State Henry Kissinger and Alexander M. Haig called on the United
States and China to take measures to end unnecessary
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger, in an article published in the Washington Post
Tuesday, said a sino-American conflict would be avoidable and
damaging to both sides.
</P>
<P>
"The prospects of world peace, stability and progress will be
hazarded if the current unnecessary rush toward confrontation is
not reversed by both sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Alexander Haig said like any other two big
countries, there exist differences between the U.S. and China, but
the two countries can work together to establish a stable
relationship as it is in the interest of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Haig, while meeting which Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing here
Tuesday, pointed out that it is wrong for Lee Teng-hui to put
forward the "State-to-State" doctrine, which has created troubles
for all the sides concerned.
</P>
<P>
He said Taiwan is the core issue between the U.S. and China and
the U.S. government should insist on its "One China" policy and
abide by the three communiques governing U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, Henry Kissinger agreed that it is "the
most explosive issue" between the U.S. and China.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger noted that from World War II, American presidents
have affirmed Taiwan to be a part of China in one form or
another and the United States, like the vast majority of the
world's governments, has recognized Beijing as the legitimate
government of all of China.
</P>
<P>
"Were Taiwan to achieve formal American recognition of a
separate status, as its president now seems to seek, this would
surely lead to some kind of military clash that, whatever its
outcome, would permanently rupture Sino-American relations and
isolate America in Asia and probably the world." said Kissinger.
"Taiwan would be less, not more, secure in such an environment."
</P>
<P>
He said with respect to Taiwan, the U.S. government should take
three steps: to leave no ambiguity about America's opposition to
the use of force; to make clear that there is no change in
America's longstanding acceptance of the principle of one China;
to insist on Taiwanese restraint in challenging a framework that,
in fact, ensures their autonomy and without which events may well
run out of control.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger called on the presidents of the two countries to try
to defuse the immediate crisis and begin to place Sino-American
relations on a solid basis in the coming talks in New Zealand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
