<HEADLINE> Berger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin spokes by telephone to U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday and denied he and his family had any link with an
international money laundering scandal, reported in Wednesday's
Washington Post, a top U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
"Yeltsin denied those reports," national Security Advisor Sandy
Berger told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said Yeltsin and Clinton "talked about money laundering,
corruption" in an hour-long conversation.
</P>
<P>
Berger said he was not sure whether Yeltsin made his comments
in response to an inquiry by Clinton or volunteered them.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the scandal will be
on the agenda when Clinton meets Russian Prime Minister Vladimir
Putin at an Asia-pacific economic summit this weekend in New
Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
