<HEADLINE> FARC Denies Presence in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia (FARC) Wednesday denied any presence in Ecuador and
showed concern over the fact that Quito may have offered the use
of the "Manta" military base to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Sectors in Ecuador" carry out orders from the United States
and agree to become involved in the armed conflict in Colombia,
said a spokesman for the FARC, Captain Raul, in a television
interview with an Ecuadorian television network.
</P>
<P>
The FARC spokesman considered that in a recent tour of South
America, U.S. anti-drugs chief Barry McCaffrey was sounding out
the possibility of help from within the region, for a possible
military attack against the Colombian guerrillas by the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"The Ecuadorian government gave the U.S. permission to transfer
the majority of what they had in Panama, this is very serious, not
only for the revolutionary process in Colombia and the FARC, but
also for the population of Ecuador", he added.
</P>
<P>
Captain Raul considered as "very serious", the possibility
that the people of both Ecuador and Colombia will be used as
"cannon fodder for an (eventual) war which is not theirs".
</P>
<P>
The FARC are the largest rebel group in Colombia, followed in
numbers by the National Liberation Army (ELN).
</P>
<P>
The United States are assembling a military installation in the
Manta base, in the province of Manabi, west of Ecuador, on the
Ecuadorian border with the south of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The rebel spokesman denied the accusation by U.S. officials
that the FARC are involved in the trafficking of drugs.
</P>
<P>
In other extracts from the interview, Captain Raul said that
the FARC are not in league with either Fidel Castro of Cuba, or
Hugo Chavez of Venezuela, although they do have common goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
