<HEADLINE> Special OAU Summit Opens in Sirte, Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIRTE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A special OAU summit opened in
Libya's seaport city of Sirte on Wednesday, centering on ways of
restructuring the charter of the pan-African body to enhance unity
among member states.
</P>
<P>
According to Ibrahim Daggash, spokesman of the Organization of
African Unity, 43 African heads of state including Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi were present at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of Algeria, Tunisia and Sudan were among those who
attend Wednesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, whose country is the
current chair of the OAU, opened the meeting, saying there could be
no Africa unity without peace on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot move forward as long as there are conflicts in Africa
and as long as there are refugees," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, Gadhafi has been trying to lodge more support
from Africa than from the Arab world as he believes African leaders
stood by him during his confrontation with the West over Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
Besides reframing the OAU's charter, the summit, which ends
Thursday, will also discuss Gadhafi's proposal to unite Africa by
promoting economic cooperation and building better transportation
links. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
