<HEADLINE> Cyprus Offers Aid to Help Quake-hit Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government
Wednesday decided to offer 1 million U.S dollars in aid to Greece
to help it carry out relief operations following a devastating
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
A Cypriot team comprising engineers and fire-fighters is
heading to Greece, whose capital Athens was hit Tuesday by the
earthquake which was measured at 5.9 degrees on the Richter scale
and has killed at least 50 people and left some 120 people trapped
in fallen buildings.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou told reporters
after the weekly cabinet meeting that Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides Wednesday telephoned Greek Premier Costas Simitis and
informed him of the government decision.
</P>
<P>
He said Clerides conveyed to Simitis Cyprus' readiness to
"offer any assistance which may be required, ranging from
doctors, nurses, engineers, pharmaceuticals, tents or anything
else."
</P>
<P>
Messages of solidarity with the people and the government of
Greece were also sent by Cypriot political parties.
</P>
<P>
Greece is the strong supporter for the Greek Cypriot-dominated
Cypriot government on the Mediterranean island. Turkish Cypriots
established a breakaway republic in northern Cyprus, which is only
recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
