<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Official Blasts Statements by Iraqi Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Kuwaiti official
on Wednesday lashed out at an Iraqi newspaper for its article on
the latest rapprochement efforts between Kuwait and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait "has been used to hostile statements made by Iraqi
media as they sometimes cause confusion," Sulaiman Majid
Al-Shaheen, the Kuwaiti minister of state for foreign affairs, was
quoted as saying by the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi newspaper alleged that Kuwait urged Jordan, which
sided with Iraq in the 1991 Gulf War, to cooperate with it in the
efforts to isolate Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti News Agency did not mention the name of the paper
and the date when the article was published.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaheen said his country has "the right and sovereignty to
deal with any Arab or foreign states freely and sincerely."
</P>
<P>
He also urged those who "cast doubt over the Kuwaiti policy to
refrain from making unjustified statements."
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein wound up a landmark two-day
official visit to Kuwait Monday, closing a decade-long
Jordanian-Kuwaiti estrangement.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaheen is due in Saudi Red Sea port city of Jiddah on
Friday to attend the foreign ministers' meeting of the Gulf Arab
countries aimed at coordinating positions of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states ahead of an Arab League session due in Cairo
next week.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaheen said that the GCC meeting will tackle, among other
issues, the consequences of Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, including
the issue of Kuwaiti nationals allegedly still held in captivity
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia
and the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
