<HEADLINE> Oman Denies Plans to Hold Exercise With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- An official of the Omani
Defense Ministry Wednesday denied media reports that Oman is
planning to hold joint navy maneuvers with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"What was carried by the media is totally untrue," the Oman
News Agency quoted the official as saying in Muscat on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a spokesman for Oman's Royal Navy was quoted by
some reports as saying that preparations are under way for the
joint naval exercise that will take place "soon".
</P>
<P>
"The Iran-Oman maneuvers will be useful for ensuring regional
peace and stability," commander of the Iranian navy Admiral Abbas
Mohtaj was also quoted as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Oman agreed last year to carry out military and
logistical cooperation, including joint war games, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The alleged plan of military exercise between Oman and Iran
could upset the United Arab Emirates (UAE), which has a dispute
with Iran over Tehran's occupation of the three islands of Abu
Mousa and the Greater and Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is against rapprochement with Iran by Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) countries unless the islands dispute is solved. It
is especially opposed to GCC military cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Besides the UAE, the GCC includes Oman, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
