<HEADLINE> S. African Ruling Party Condemns Violence in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The African National
Congress (ANC) , South Africa's ruling party, said in a statement
here Wednesday that "it is deeply shocked and profoundly disturbed
by the continued deterioration of the situation in East Timor".
</P>
<P>
The ANC, as a firm believer in the principles of democracy and
human rights, "unequivocally condemns this violence and carnage in
the strongest possible terms," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The random attacks by the 'pro-Indonesia' militia on
'pro-independence' supporters are totally unacceptable. The
democratic will of the people cannot be undermined in this way,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It called on the government of Indonesia to take measures to
contain the situation, saying that "we urge the Indonesian
government to do the correct thing and intervene positively in the
protection of democracy and in order to eliminate any possible
allegations of compliance in these dark and anti- democratic
actions".
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the United Nations Secretary-General, Kofi
Annan, to convene a special sitting in order to facilitate an end
to the disorder and to protect the rights of the people of East
Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
