<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana President Lifts State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Botswana President Festus
Mogae Tuesday lifted the state of emergency to enable 60,000
registered voters to vote in the October 16 general elections.
</P>
<P>
"The date of the general elections remains as announced," the
Presidential Office was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency was declared last Thursday to enable the
 parliament, dissolved prior to the forthcoming elections, to
reconvene and to pass an amendment to the Electoral Act for the
Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) to continue its work and
put the 60,000 names on the voters' roll.
</P>
<P>
The 60,000 voters registered in a supplementary registration
drive but their names were not included in the voters' roll by the
time Mogae issued a writ for the election to be held on October
16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
