<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-Egyptian Accord to Boost Relations: German </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A partnership agreement to be
signed between the European Union (EU) and Egypt will promote the
development of bilateral political and economic cooperation
between the two sides, the German ambassador said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Peter Michael Dingens told a meeting held here on German trade
and investment policies that the agreement "constitutes a strong
basis for" the EU-Egyptian relations and trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Dingens said he is hopeful that the accord will be initialed
ahead of Egypt's September 26 referendum on President Hosni
Mubarak's nomination by the People's Assembly (Parliament) for a
fourth six-year term.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized by the Egyptian Businessmen
Association and aimed at helping Egyptian businessmen get
acquainted with German trade and investment policies, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After almost four years of negotiations, the EU foreign
ministers and an Egyptian ministerial committee in charge of the
agreement endorsed the pact separately in June and July.
</P>
<P>
The accord provides for more open trade, coordination in many
economic and financial areas, a political dialog and joint efforts
to combat money laundering and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Dingens said Egypt is a major partner of EU in the Barcelona
process for the Euro-Med cooperation in view of its political and
strategic weight.
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU nations and 12 Mediterranean countries, including
Egypt, kicked off the Barcelona process in a 1995 conference in
Barcelona, Spain. The participants decided to forge close
cooperation in political, economic, social and security fields.
Their key aim is to set up a free trade area by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Germany is interested in opening up European markets to
Egyptian products, the German diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Germany is keen on inviting Egypt to display products at
exhibitions held in the country, Dingens said, adding that the
expo 2000 will be held in the German city of Hanover with Egypt
pitching in with a large pavilion.
</P>
<P>
The EU is Egypt's largest trade partner, accounting for 638
million U.S. dollars of Egypt's exports and 3.6 billion dollars of
its imports in the first half of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
