<HEADLINE> Sudan Hopes for Positive U.S. Response to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Othman Ismail has expressed hope that the U.S. will
receive positively the Egyptian-Libyan initiative for resolving
the Sudanese crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ismail made the remarks in the Libyan capital of Tripoli after
meeting with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa and Libyan
Assistant Secretary of the General People's Committee on Foreign
Liaison for African Affairs Ali El-Turieki on the sidelines of the
ministerial meeting of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The recent Egyptian-Libyan initiative calls for a permanent
cease-fire and a national peace conference in an effort to end the
16-year-old civil war between the Sudanese government and the
south rebels. The war and the ensuing famine have claimed nearly 2
million lives in the poor African state.
</P>
<P>
Ismail said the initiative is in line with the proposal of the
Inter-Governmental Authority of Development (IGAD) and Khartoum
will adhere to it.
</P>
<P>
The initiative also calls for coordination with the U.S., the
Sudanese News Agency quoted Ismail as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ismail said a preparatory meeting on Sudanese national dialog
will be held in Cairo in October.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent Cairo talks between Moussa and
Sudanese opposition leaders, including Johan Garang, the leader of
the opposition Sudanese People's Liberation Army, Ismail said the
meetings led to some amendments in the timetable for the upcoming
preparatory committee convention.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Moussa voiced Egypt's determination to continue
its efforts to coordinate the position with countries concerned
through the ongoing OAU extraordinary session and the IGAD.
</P>
</TEXT>
