<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Clinton Discuss Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and his U.S. counterpart, Bill Clinton, agreed Wednesday that
bilateral ties "should not be held hostage to internal political
battles," the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders stated such a position during their telephone
conversation Wednesday, the Interfax news agency quoted the
Kremlin press service as saying.
</P>
<P>
The presidential press service said that "the unleashing of
boisterous campaigns does not contribute to the buildup of mutual
trust."
</P>
<P>
It was apparently referring to Western and Russian media
reports of Russian money laundering through several U.S. banks and
alleged high-level corruption.
</P>
<P>
Russian authorities said domestic politics in the two countries
were behind the media frenzy over the scandals.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Clinton that a group of Russian law enforcement
agencies' officials is being sent to the U.S. "to work out
interactively with American counterparts issues, related to a
number of publications that have appeared in the U.S. media in
recent time," the press service said.
</P>
<P>
The presidents also discussed a time-table for early bilateral
contacts at various levels, the press service said.
</P>
<P>
It said that special attention was paid to the planned meeting
between Clinton and Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin during
the Asian and Pacific Cooperation (APEC) forum in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed arms reduction and bilateral
cooperation in the fight against international terrorism, Interfax
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
