<HEADLINE> France Wants Full U.N. Role in E. Timor: Chirac </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
said on Wednesday that France wants the United Nations Security
Council to take its full responsibility in East Timor, which has
been plunged into a chaos for one week.
</P>
<P>
"I solemnly call on (Indonesian) President (Yusuf) Habibie and
the Indonesian civil and military authorities to respect their
commitment and to guarantee the security of all in East Timor, or
take of risk of having the international financial aid to
Indonesia put into doubt," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has rejected that U.N. deploy a
peacekeeping force in East Timor, after pro-Indonesian militiamen
have put the territory under an absolute rule of terror in
collaboration with the Indonesian army and police.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that the people of East Timor have freely expressed
their choice during the U.N.-sponsored referendum on the future of
the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
"The choice which was made through the votes should be
respected. The security and the freedom of everyone should be
guaranteed. Violence and murders should stop," he said during a
meeting of the government ministers.
</P>
<P>
Chirac described the current situation in East Timor as
"intolerable acts of massive and murderous persecutions."
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party has called on the government to stop all
military cooperation with and suspend financial aid to Indonesia
until peace and security are reestablished in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party will organize a rally in Paris Wednesday
evening to express support and sympathy to the people of East
Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
