<HEADLINE> U.N. Ready to Assist Keeping Order in E. Timor: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Wednesday the United Nations is planning to go
ahead with international intervention in East Timor as the
situation there is deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
He said he told Indonesian President B.J. Habibie that "if they
(Indonesians) are unable to maintain law and order, then they
would have to accept international assistance... and this is
something the (Security) Council will press."
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks during a Security Council session on
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
A five-member team sent Monday by the Security Council is now
in Jakarta and it has had several meetings, while President
Habibie is going to see the team Wednesday afternoon, the U.N.
chief told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said only time will tell if the new troops sent by the
Indonesian Government to replace those in East Timor will improve
the security situation there.
</P>
<P>
"I think that there is too much killing, we cannot stand by and
allow the people of East Timor to be killed," Annan said,
expressing U.N.'s determination to fully implement the results of
the August 30 ballot in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Violent activities by anti-independence militias following the
ballot have resulted in life losses, people's displacement and
threat to the security to the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET)
which organized the ballot.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is in favor of East Timor's independence
instead of special autonomy within Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
