<HEADLINE> Mitchell Says Deadlock on N.Ireland Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. mediator George Mitchell
said on Wednesday that he still thought the problems plaguing the
Northern Ireland peace process could be solved.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. senator made the remarks in the Northern
Ireland capital Belfast after three days of listening to British
and Irish officials and rival parties at odds over whether Sinn
Fein should enter government before its Irish Republican Army
(IRA) allies disarmed.
</P>
<P>
"I am encouraged by the seriousness of purpose and
determination with which they are entering this review," he said
in a statement released after he left for the United States.
</P>
<P>
But he acknowledged "deep differences" among all groups over
how the Good Friday agreement could be implemented.
</P>
<P>
He is due back in Belfast next Monday to resume the talks.
</P>
<P>
The biggest barrier to implementing the landmark Good Friday
Agreement signed in April, 1998, is that Ulster Unionists in the
most powerful Protestant party refuse to set up a power-sharing
executive with Sinn Fein until the IRA hands in its weapons.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell had guided two years of tortuous talks leading up to
last year's accord.
</P>
<P>
He remained optimistic at mid-week despite expressions of
pessimism from Protestant politicians, including Ulster Unionist
leader and provincial First Minister David Trimble. 
</P>
