<HEADLINE> First Briton Charged Under New "Air Rage" Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A 36-year-old man has become
the first person to be charged under Britain's tough new "air
rage" laws which came into effect last week, the Reuters reported
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation is aimed at passengers who threaten, insult
or abuse airline crew members or interfere with their duties. The
maximum penalty is two years' imprisonment or an unlimited fine.
</P>
<P>
Tony Chandler, aged 36, was charged with being drunk on an
aircraft, acting in a disruptive manner.
</P>
<P>
"He's the first person to be charged with the new offense and
he will appear in court on October 13," spokeswoman for Manchester
police said.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place on Tuesday's 9:45 a.m.(0745 GMT) KLM
flight from Amsterdam to Manchester.
</P>
<P>
Following take-off, one of the passengers became verbally
abusive after he was refused more alcohol -- the cabin crew
surmised that he was intoxicated, the captain called ahead to make
sure the police were there to arrest him on landing, said a KLM
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The government introduced the new legislation in an attempt to
curb an alarming increase in air rage attacks which British
Airways claims have increased by 400 percent in the past four
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
