<HEADLINE> Thai Banks Prepared for Date-Related Computer Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- No commercial banks in
Thailand would be affected by the so-called "Nines Problem"
supposed to occur Thursday, the Thai News Agency (TNA) Wednesday
quoted a senior official from the Bank of Thailand as saying.
</P>
<P>
There have been fears that the date-related computer glitch or
millennium bug may strike for the first time Thursday when the
calendar turns to the four nines -- September 9, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kitti Pattanapongpibul, deputy governor of the Bank of Thailand
(BOT), was quoted as saying that the Nines Problem would not
affect commercial banks because the banks' systems had been fixed
and were ready to cope with all date-related problems.
</P>
<P>
He also said the banks were now ready for services when the
clock strikes midnight on December 31.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Thai Airways International said the country's
airliner plans to maintain normal flights on Thursday and to fly
over the millennium period.
</P>
<P>
The airliner has done testing with the technical glitches
already, which have found no risk of the millennium bug to the
navigation system, an official from the airways' information
technology service said.
</P>
<P>
The THAI captains are to fly 119 international routes and 107
domestic flights on Thursday. They have no plan to suspend flights
over the millennium period either, the TNA said. 
</P>
