<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Slams U.N. Decision to Use Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Wednesday
lodged "the strongest protest" with the U.N. Security Council
against a regulation by the U.N. special representative for Kosovo
to permit the use of foreign currencies as legal tender in Kosovo,
the Serbian province, and demanded the Security Council
immediately cancel the decision.
</P>
<P>
The protest was contained in a letter to the president of the
Security Council from Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of
the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations. The letter was
officially published here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic, in the letter, said, "The regulation constitutes a
most flagrant violation of Security Council resolution 1244 (1999)
and an attack on the sovereignty, monetary and financial unity and
the economic, legal and, by extension, territorial integrity of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
"Alongside the abolition of the Yugoslav monetary and financial
laws and control, the permission is a crass excess of the mandate
by the Special Representative of the Secretary-General and amounts
to the constitution of aggression by other means, aimed at
separating Kosovo from the constitutional and legal whole of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These illegal and arbitrary acts of the Special Representative
of the Secretary-General are outside the bounds of relevant
behavior and seriously threaten the process of finding a solution
to Kosovo on the basis of Security Council resolution 1244," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, adopted on June 10, demands all Member States
respect the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia calls on the
Security Council to condemn the regulation most energetically and
to cancel it immediately," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the United Nations has legalized the use of
foreign currencies for payments and contracts in the Serbian
province in what the United Nations called "another major step to
restart economy of Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
The new legislative act, signed Thursday by the U.N. special
representative for Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner, allows the use of all
currencies, including the Yugoslav dinar, while lifting past legal
restrictions on the use of all foreign currencies, the U.N.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important first step towards the creation of
functioning banking, payments and fiscal systems in Kosovo," said
Joly Dixon, the U.N. deputy special representative in charge of
economic reconstruction in Kosovo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
