<HEADLINE> BoE Raises Interest Rates To 5.25 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England (BoE)
Wednesday surprised financial markets by raising Britain's 'base
rate' by a quarter point to 5.25 percent, the first rise since
June last year.
</P>
<P>
The BoE's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) cited world demand,
the strength of consumption, the booming housing market and
continuing tight conditions in the labor market as reasons for the
rate move.
</P>
<P>
The UK banks moved quickly to raise their mortgage and base
interest rates immediately after the BoE increased its key short
term rate.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares fell 2.15 percent in early afternoon trade on fears
that rising interest rates may slow loan growth and hurt credit
quality, helping drag the FTSE 100 down 1.3 percent by 1345 GMT.
</P>
<P>
Halifax Plc, Britain's largest mortgage bank, was the first to
jump, lifting its key variable mortgage rate by 14 basis points to
6.99 percent.
</P>
<P>
The BoE had last changed its 'base rate' in June, when it cut
the rate by a quarter point to of 5 percent, which was a 22-year
low.  
</P>
</TEXT>
