<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Indonesia to Restore Order in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday urged Indonesia to restore peace and order in East Timor
or to invite an international peacekeeping force to do that.
</P>
<P>
"The point we have made very clearly and forcefully to the
Indonesian government is that they need to demonstrate that they
are prepared to assert control in East Timor or we believe they
should invite an international presence to restore order," White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been no indication that unrest had eased in
East Timor and Washington was "pressing the (Indonesian)
government at all levels and through all channels that they do
face a choice here."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States was considering what level of
assistance would be needed if the international peacekeeping
force was formed.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart also said that U.S. and international economic aid
to Indonesia depended on whether it could quell unrest and
restore order in East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
