<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unlikely to Send Troops to East Timor: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States is not
planning to send peacekeeping troops to turmoil-ridden East Timor,
but is discussing support for any such international force with
other nations, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have to be selective where we commit our forces and,
under the circumstances, this is not an area that we are
prepared to commit forces," Cohen told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is not planning on any insertion of
peacekeeping forces. We are coordinating and talking to the
Australians and others who would be interested in a peacekeeping
force should the Indonesian government invite such a force in
and should the United Nations approve it," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was up to the government of Indonesia to bring
peace to East Timor or to invite an international peacekeeping
force in under the auspices of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that there would be major economic and other
financial consequences for Indonesia if it failed to bring peace
to East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
