<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian FM Meets U.N. Security Council Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas Wednesday met a five-member United Nations Security
Council mission here and exchanged views on the latest
developments in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"We had a good discussion. They submitted their views and
conveyed a message from the U.N. secretary general and Security
Council members. On the other hand, I filled them in on the latest
developments, especially on the reasons for the declaration of a
military emergency in East Timor," Alatas told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government declared a state of emergency in East
Timor Tuesday morning following serious violence in the territory.
</P>
<P>
The military emergency status was imposed on East Timor on the
basis of careful considerations, Alatas said, adding that the
question of sending a U.N. peacekeeping force to East Timor did
not arise.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said during the second phase of the East Timor
settlement process the Indonesian government continued to be
responsible for what was happening in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
According to an accord reached by Indonesia, Portugal and U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan in New York on May 5, the second
phase of the settlement process means the period between the
announcement of a ballot result favoring independence and the
endorsement of such a ballot outcome by the Indonesian People's
Consultative Assembly which is to meet starting October.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Martin Andjaba of Namibia, leader of the U.N.
Security Council's mission, said his group and Alatas exchanged
views on how to end the bloodshed in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"We have been assured that the Indonesian government is
committed. I would not go into any details now because our
discussion is continuing," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council team consisted of U.N. envoys from
Britain, Slovenia, Malaysia, Namibia and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The mission, which was organized after an emergency Security
Council meeting on September 6, arrived in Jakarta on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The mission was scheduled also to meet with President B.J.
Habibie and Chief of National Defense Forces Gen. Wiranto on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The violence in East Timor flared up following the announcement
in New York on September 4 that 78.5 percent of voters in the
U.N.-organized August 30 direct ballot had opted for independence
from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in
1976, has been seen by the U.N. General Assembly as a
non-self-governing territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
