<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide PC Unit Volume Expected to Grow 24 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Unit volume in the
worldwide PC market in the third quarter is expected to grow 24.8
percent from a year ago, said market researcher International Data
Corp.(IDC) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Market expansion will continue to be led by robust global
consumer demand for ever-cheaper PCs, healthy growth in Asian
markets and the strong U.S. economy, the market research company
said.
</P>
<P>
Unit shipments are expected to rise 7.2 percent in the third
quarter from 10.9 million PCs in the second quarter. In the second
quarter last year, PC makers deliver eight million computers.
</P>
<P>
Japan has the highest year-to-year growth rate in the second
quarter with an increase of 39 percent, according to IDC, which is
forecasting a 32 percent increase in PC shipments in the country
during the current quarter. Western Europe's PC demand is expected
to grow 16.3 percent in the third quarter, while U.S. PC volumes
will be up 12.2 percent to 12.2 million units in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
PC shipments in the Asia-Pacific market, excluding Japan, will
be up 34.43 percent in the third quarter compared with last year,
IDC said. China, India, South Korea and Australia are expected to
drive the growth in the region. But political unrest in India,
Indonesia and Malaysia could hamper the region's growth in the
second half of this year, said the research firm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
