<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Releases Palestinian Prisoners Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel decided Wednesday to
release 200 Palestinian prisoners Thursday morning, the first
step in the implementation of a peace accord signed by Israel and
the Palestinians last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli committee headed by the director-general of the
Justice Ministry formally approved the list of the first batch
of Palestinian prisoners to be released, a government statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The 200 prisoners will be brought from various prisons in
Israel to military checkpoints outside Palestinian self-rule towns
 in the West Bank Thursday morning, according to Israeli radio
reports.
</P>
<P>
The release of the 200 prisoners is in the first stage of the
modified Wye land-for-security deal signed by Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yesser Arafat in Sharm el-Sheikh, Egypt, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is originally due to take effect in a week after
its signing.
</P>
<P>
Israel's parliament overwhelmingly approved the agreement
Wednesday night, paving the way for three stages of Israeli
redeployments in 11 percent of the West Bank. The cabinet
ratified the accord by a large margin Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 120-member Knesset voted 52 in favor, 23 against, with 2
abstention, to approve the agreement. The other Knesset members
did not take part in the voting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, the cabinet voted 17-1, with one
abstention, to give go-ahead to the implementation of the
agreement's first stage, in which Israel will also transfer 7
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians besides the
release of prisoners. Four ministers were absent from the
voting.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the decision to hand over parts of the biblical
Land of Israel was not easy, but that it is in Israel's best
interest to move toward comprehensive peace agreements with its
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Israeli negotiator Gilad Sher has said that the first
redeployment will be carried out on September 13, the 6th
anniversary of the signing of the historic Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
The release of Palestinian prisoners had been a thorny
issue in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. Israel has insisted
that it would not release those Palestinians who killed Israelis
or belong to Islamic militant group Hamas or Jihad.
</P>
<P>
Among the 200 prisoners to be release Thursday, 150 were
jailed for killing Palestinians who had cooperated with Israeli
security services, 15 were involved in the wounding of Israelis,
Israel Radio said. The others were jailed for other security
offensives, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
A further 150 prisoners are due to be freed on October
8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
