<HEADLINE> Clinton Questioned in Labor Secretary Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S President Bill Clinton
was questioned by an independent counsel Wednesday in the federal
investigation over allegations of influence-peddling and campaign
finance improprieties against Labor Secretary Alexis Herman.
</P>
<P>
The interview was conducted by Independent Counsel Ralph
Lancaster and two associates, John Kotelly and David Barry.
</P>
<P>
"The Interview lasted one hour and was conducted under oath.
Consistent with prior practice, no further statement about the
interview will be made," the White House said in a written
statement.
</P>
<P>
Lancaster, who was named to the post of independent counsel in
May 1998, is investigating allegations Herman solicited illegal
campaign contributions of 250,000 dollars and engaged in influence
peddling while she was a White House aide during President
Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
Herman has denied the allegations and Clinton has said he is
confident that investigators will conclude that Herman did nothing
wrong.
</P>
<P>
The charges focus on claims by Cameroon-born businessman
Laurent Yene that he delivered an envelope of cash to Herman's
home, representing a 10 percent cut of consulting fees he earned
from a client seeking a federal license for a satellite telephone
system.
</P>
<P>
Yene also claimed that Herman directed Vanessa Weaver, a close
friend of Herman, to obtain campaign contributions for the
Democratic National Committee from a firm.
</P>
<P>
Lancaster's investigation is one of five independent-counsel
probes of government officials that remain at least technically
open following the expiration of the independent-counsel law in
June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
