<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Senator Launches Presidential Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Senator Bill
Bradley Wednesday formally launched his campaign for the
Democratic presidential nominations in his hometown of Crystal
City, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
"I feel an urgent need to seize this moment in history, to
strengthen the weak and to challenge the strong to lead us into
our full greatness as a nation," said the former New Jersey
senator in a speech. He is the only Democratic rival of Vice
President Al Gore in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
"I'm more interested in leadership than polls and politics,''
he said. "I believe we need a new kind of leadership."
</P>
<P>
Bradley, who promised a "different kind of campaign", stressed
a need for racial harmony, better health care and a stronger
education system.
</P>
<P>
Bradley trails Gore not only in the polls but also in fund
raising and party endorsement.
</P>
<P>
Bradley, 56, was an all-American basketball star at Princeton
University, a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford University and senator
from New Jersey for 18 years before he became the only
Democrat to challenge Gore for the nomination.  
</P>
</TEXT>
