<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Pledges Telecom Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has
reaffirmed its commitment to liberalizing the telecommunications
sector and immediately opening its cellular phone market to
operators.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Fernandes, deputy minister of Transport and
Communications, made the pledge monday while explaining the
government strategy to the Parliamentary Commission on Economic
Activities and Services, a report carried by Wednesday's issue of
the independent newsheet " Metical" said.
</P>
<P>
Currently the company M-Cel, which is a joint venture between
TDM, Mozambique' s publicly owned telecommunications company, and
Detecom, Germany's company, has monopolized the cellular phone
network in southern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to open this market immediately to other
operators, Fernandes said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister explained that the main reason for
abandoning the state monopoly over the fixed phone network is that
the state simply does not have the money needed to make the
necessary new investments in telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The external sources of funding, on which TDM had relied in the
past, are drying up, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The solution we think correct is to open up to other
operators, and do away with the state monopoly", he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
