<HEADLINE> Canada Not to Take Unilateral Move in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada will not move
unilaterally into the current conflict of East Timor, Prime
Minister Jean Chretien said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to move in a multilateral way. I don't think that
Canada can move with troops in East Timor," he told reporters
after announcing the appointment of Adrienne Clarkson as governor
general in the foyer of the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
Chretien made the remarks a day before leaving for New Zealand
for the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit, where some
countries are likely to press Indonesia to allow peacekeepers into
East Timor, according to Canadian media reports.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian army declared a state of emergency in East Timor
Tuesday morning amid serious violence sparked after the
announcement of the direct autonomy ballot on September 4.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Defense Minister Wiranto has reiterated that the
Indonesian government can get its own security forces to restore
law and order in East Timor. 
</P>
