<HEADLINE> IMF Loan for Angola Needs "Patience" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A delegate from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) said here Wednesday that Angola
should be more patient with the possible IMF loan despite the
positive contact with the country.
</P>
<P>
Paulo Neuhaus, head of an IMF mission to Angola, made the
statement before leaving here for Washington, where he will remit
the results of the negotiations aimed at starting an economic
program monitored by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Neuhaus said that during the visit, his delegation made
appraisals on the impact of the measures taken by the Angolan
government in the ambit of structure readjustment, with an aim to
reanimate the Angolan economy.
</P>
<P>
Those measures in financial and monetary systems and exchange
control are "opportune", he said, but pointing out that the
country should be more patient, because the results of the
measures are, after all, not of " immediate character".
</P>
<P>
Neuhaus said it is a "very positive" sign that the Angolan
government has made strong engagement in discussion with the IMF
on all questions, which could rapidly lead to the start of the
monitored program.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the right way for the initiation of the monitored
program by the fund, from January of 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
The monitored program will permit IMF to participate in shaping
Angola's economic policy and make evaluation on some goals of the
government's program for 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the program established by IMF, the Angolan government
should adopt such policies as lowering the inflation rate,
reforming the tax system and cutting the administrative
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
A full implementation of the monitored program will make Angola
 accessible to another program called Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility (ESAF), which has been established by the IMF
to provide long- term and low-interest (0.5%) loans to the
countries in low water, encouraging them to reform their economic
structure.
</P>
<P>
During the seven-day visit to Angola, the IMF mission held
talks with the Angolan government on questions relating to
financial policy, monetary system, exchange control, external
debts, inflation, petroleum price and budget transparency.
</P>
<P>
Future negotiations will take place in Washington following the
annual meeting of the IMF and the World Bank to be held late this
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
