<HEADLINE> Romania's GDP Down by 3.9 Percent in First Semester </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of Romania registered in the first semester of 1999 was
180.403 trillion lei, 3.9 percent lower than that in the same
period of last year, showed the latest statistics released by the
government.
</P>
<P>
The drop greatly surpassed the anticipated target of 2 percent
set by the government for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
In all branches of the economy, except for agriculture,
forestry, fishing and forest exploitation, operations performed
during the first semester of 1999 were under the level registered
last year. The most pronounced decrease was in constructions (-14
percent), followed by industry (-5.9 percent) and services (-2.3
percent).
</P>
<P>
Gross added value registered in agriculture, forestry, fishing
and forest exploitation had an increase of 0.8 percent compared to
the first semester of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Imports of goods and services in the first semester 1999 of was
almost at the same level with that of the previous year (-0.6
percent), but exports of goods and services were 7.6 percent
higher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Central Bank Submits 1998 Business Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of Romania
submitted early this week its business report for 1998 to the
Parliament, drawing attention to the fact that the real economy
retreated for the second consecutive year, with the only success
in the significant decrease of the inflation rate against 1997.
</P>
<P>
The decline of industry and constructions, as well as of
agricultural production below the achievements of the previous
year, and higher unemployment were reflected in lower GDP. The
domestic debt of the state rose, and the unfavorable status of
foreign trade aggravated the decline, the local Nine O'clock daily
informed on Wednesday citing the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bank stresses that arrears to the state and social
insurance budgets were further tolerated in 1998, while certain
loss-making companies benefited from rescheduling of debts to the
state, energy suppliers and banks.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the salary policy was permissive and in contradiction
with economic reality, aggravating the serious imbalances of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, GDP fell 7.3 percent against 1997's 338,670
billion lei(about 30 billion U.S. dollars). The sector of the
economy with the major participation in GDP formation was that of
services. This trend reflects structural changes in the economy,
the bank estimated in these conditions, industry lost supremacy in
creating GDP. In industry, statistics point to a fall of
production and of the contribution to the formation of state
revenues, for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
The central bank pointed out that restructuring and
privatization were the vulnerable points of the reform program in
1998 too. Nevertheless, these processes were firmly relaunched by
the end of the year. Restructuring loss- making industrial
companies and non-profitable state farms did not yield enough
results in order to have a good impact on the general status of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Decreasing the annual rate of inflation, from 151 in 1997 down
to 59.1 percent, was the outcome of a consistently restrictive
attitude.
</P>
<P>
1999 can be considered a decisive year for Romania's
transition, the report specified. The central bank announced that
GDP might fall around 3-3.5 percent, while the unemployment rate
could exceed 12 percent. If the authorities act in a firm way, the
unfavorable trend could be interrupted in the second half of the
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
