<HEADLINE> Greece Announces Measures to Help Earthquake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis Wednesday announced measures to provide support and
restitution to those left homeless by Tuesday's powerful
earthquake which hit northern Athens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Simitis said that each family
left homeless by the earthquake would receive an immediate lump
sum payment of 200,000 drachmas (about 662.3 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local government authorities would be charged with setting up
camping sites for the establishment of tent cities for the
temporarily homeless, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that the state would undertake to cover one
third of the cost of the rebuilding or repair of damaged homes and
would also provide interest-free 15-year loans.
</P>
<P>
Also available would be subsidized loans for those
self-employed professionals and commercial enterprises hurt by the
quake.
</P>
<P>
So far, the death toll from Tuesday's earthquake measuring 5.9
on the Richter scale has risen to 63, and 2,006 persons were
injuried and 10,000 left homeless.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 tents and makeshift shelters had been delivered
while 1,500 firemen and 2,000 soldiers were involved in rescue
work, along with army engineers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
