<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A British warship was preparing
Wednesday to head for the waters around East Timor to support any
United Nations peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
The ship was dispatched to the island by British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, who was worried by East Timor's "descent into chaos."
</P>
<P>
Britain would also send a team of military advisers to help
plan for the peacekeeping force, a spokesman for Blair told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The destroyer HMS Glasgow, a Type 42 guided missile destroyer
with around 280 men on board, is currently in Malaysian waters.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the warship would sail within hours for East
Timor where it was expected to join Australian vessels to provide
support "as the United Nations sees fit."
</P>
<P>
"It will have a communications facility and command and control
support as well," he said, adding that the ship would take some
days to reach East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of East Timorese have been killed since the province
voted overwhelmingly last week to end 23 years of Indonesian rule.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Indonesia has ruled out any early deployment of
foreign peacekeepers, but Blair's spokesman said Britain would
push hard to win acceptance for their deployment. 
