<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended
mixed Wednesday in a mixed bag of signals on higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 2.21 at 11,036.34.
The blue chip index fell 44.32 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 6.30 at 1,344.15 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite fell 28.52 at 2,808.74.
</P>
<P>
The markets moved lower in earlier trading after the Bank of
England increased its base lending rate for the first time in more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
Investors were then encouraged by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan's speech to the Gerald R. Ford Foundation in Grand
Rapids, Mich. He did not say any ward on U.S. interest rate or
inflation.
</P>
<P>
But in the afternoon, Federal Reserve Governor Laurence Meyer
ended the optimism among investors. The governor said wage
pressures are building and the case for a third rate increase is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.84 at 621.87 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 1.28 at 792.39. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 2.34 at 435.90.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,785 down, 1,185 up and 578
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 779.24 million shares from 707.30
million in the previous session. 
</P>
