<HEADLINE> Six People Get U.N. Anti-Poverty Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) honored six people, including two
women, for their campaigns against poverty.
</P>
<P>
The awards were handed out by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and the UNDP administrator, Mark Brown, at a gala evening in the
General Assembly hall on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The six people honored in UNDP's "Race Against Poverty" for
serving as catalysts for change were:
</P>
<P>
Moodka Intrasan, a school teacher from northern Thailand, who
developed programs for poor children whose poverty might otherwise
have sent them into prostitution.
</P>
<P>
Dietrich Fischer, a retired economics and sociology professor
from Postdam, Germany, who set up a network to advise the
unemployed how to deal with threatened poverty in eastern Germany
after unification.
</P>
<P>
Victor Estrada Quispe of Bolivia for initiating agricultural,
irrigation and housing projects for 9,000 families in the rural
Andes.
</P>
<P>
Athanasie Rwamo of Burundi for finding shelter for homeless
children who wandered the streets of Bujumbura, the nation's
capital, to escape fighting in the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
Elmaz Almovna Appazova, a dentist raised in Uzbekistan, who
helped build a low-cost dental clinic for her fellow Crimean
Tarters and other returnees to Kamenka in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Abdallah Mohammed Omar Baghi of Egypt was awarded for creating
hrchaeological, tourist, handicraft and investment projects in the
desert around the Siwa oasis. 
</P>
