<HEADLINE> HK Banking Business Stood Usual on Y2K Critical Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) Thursday said that banks in Hong Kong have
reported normal operations throughout the morning.
</P>
<P>
No reports have been received so far from banks of any computer
problems arising from the transition to September 9, 1999, which
is widely regarded as one of the critical dates in connection with
the Year 2000 issue, a senior HKMA official said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the supervisory initiatives taken by the
HKMA, banks are required periodically to report to the HKMA
extensive information on their operations and on any material
exceptions they may encounter during the Year 2000 critical
periods, including September 9, 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
To provide for efficient monitoring of banks' functions during
the current critical period, the HKMA's Year 2000 Event Management
Center has been in operation since 6:00 p.m. September 8 and will
continue its monitoring exercise round the clock until the reports
from banks have been completed and assessed, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"The absence so far of any reports from banks of Year-2000-
related problems seems to be confirming our expectations that
September 9 would not produce problems for Hong Kong's banking
sector," said David Carse, deputy chief executive of the HKMA.
</P>
<P>
"The HKMA looks forward to a successful completion of the
current monitoring exercise and to continuing its work with the
banks and the general public to strive to ensure that the
millennium date change passes smoothly and without incident,"
Carse added.
</P>
<P>
No Y2K incidents was reported in Hong Kong, said the Central
Coordinating Center (CCC) for monitoring the computer bug problem
during the rollover to September 9, early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government
and various essential service sectors went on full alert during
the rollover, said Jessie Ting, deputy secretary for information
technology and broadcasting who is also the controller of the CCC.
</P>
<P>
"Both the government and the essential services providers have
made tremendous efforts to solve the Y2K problem. We have also
drawn up contingency arrangements to ensure a prompt response to
any unforeseen Y2K-induced incidents," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
