<HEADLINE> HK Initiates Workplace English Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A steering committee on the
English in the workplace campaign was set up in Hong Kong Thursday
in a bid to improve English proficiency of the local workforce.
</P>
<P>
The committee will advise the local governments on all aspects
of the planning, organization and implementation of the English in
the Workplace Campaign with a view to heightening awareness of the
importance of English and raising the standard of workplace
English in the community, said Joseph W. P. Wong, secretary for
Education and Manpower.
</P>
<P>
It will be working in collaboration with the Standing Committee
on Language Education and Research (SCOLAR), which has earmarked
around a total of 62 million HK dollars (about eight million U.S.
dollars) to support the campaign, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
"To maintain Hong Kong's competitive edge as an international
center of business, finance and tourism, our workforce must
maintain a high standard of English," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
The year-long campaign, expected to commence in January 2000,
seeks to heighten the community's overall awareness of the
importance of English at work, and of the need to maintain a high
level of bilingualism in our society," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The major elements of the Campaign will comprise a 50-million-
HK-dollar incentive grants scheme to fund English Language
training programs for employees, a business-school collaboration
program and a series of publicity programs and events aimed at
various sectors of the community, Wong added.
</P>
</TEXT>
