<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Y2K Hitch Reported in Singapore Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Various Computer systems in
Singapore successfully sailed through the critical transition to
September 9, 1999, the date the Y2K bug was likely to strike,
according to local reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a teletext broadcast titled "All Well on 9-9-99 with No Y2K
Hitch", the Television Corporation of Singapore (TCS) said the
arrival of 9-9-99, a precursor to the millennium bug, has not
caused any computer problems.
</P>
<P>
TCS quoted Singapore National Computer Board (NCB) as having
said the so-called "four 9s day" had gone smoothly overnight and
there had been no report of incidents.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the TradeNet system involving key trade
agencies such as Singapore Trade Development Board said business
was as usual for the trading community and the 2,600 registered
users of the TradeNet system, elaborating that "between 0000 hours
and 1200 hours on September 9, 1999, a total of 9,668 declarations
were processed by the system without any Y2K glitches."
</P>
<P>
TCS noted that government agencies had remained on alert in
case computer problems cropped up and they used the occasion to
rehearse their contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
Also quoting the NCB, TCS said today's zero incidence is due to
the high level of preparedness for Y2K compliance in various
sectors including the financial, telecommunications, utilities,
transportation and healthcare sectors.
</P>
<P>
The spread of nines could disrupt systems because some old
computers are programmed to read "9999" as a command to shut down.
</P>
<P>
The millennium bug also arises from old programs using only two
figures to denote the year, creating the danger of computer chaos
when clocks tick from "99" to "00" at midnight on December 31,
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
