<HEADLINE> Greek Mobile Phone Companies Blamed for Poor Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Greek Parliament President
Apostolos Kaklamanis Thursday criticized local mobile phone
companies for failing to deliver in the immediate aftermath of
Tuesday's earthquake, which killed 75 persons and injured more
than 2,000 others.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Parliament, Kaklamanis said that at a critical
moment, the mobile phone providers showed that they were not in
the position to provide even the most basic of services.
</P>
<P>
While praising the state-run Hellenic Telecommunications
Organization (OTE) for its excellent operations, he urged the
Greek government to preoccupy itself with the mobile phone
companies which began with capital of 30 billion drachmas (about 1
billion U.S. dollars) and have collected profits of trillions.
</P>
<P>
Just seconds after Tuesday's 5.9 earthquake centering in the
Mount Parnitha region, some 20 kilometers northwest of Athens, the
country's mobile phone network went dead completely, and the
companies said that the network's failure was due to overload as
people tried to reach their families. 
