<HEADLINE> Layoff Plan by Auto Tire Group Takes French City by Surprise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The surprise announcement on
Wednesday by the automobile tire group Michelin that it will lay
off 7,500 workers in Europe in three years has taken by surprise
Clermont-Ferrand, a south-central French city where the
headquarters of Michelin are based.
</P>
<P>
Michelin, one of the world's biggest automobile tire producers,
employs 75,000 workers in Europe, including 32,000 in France.
</P>
<P>
All the labor unions have protested the decision of Michelin,
whose details are yet to be made known.
</P>
<P>
Union leaders in Clermont-Ferrand said that the plan by the
management is a "blow with club" to employees, who got the news
from the press and were not pre-consulted by the employers.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that Michelin decided to down-size the labor
force after its profits rose by 17 percent in the early half this
year.
</P>
<P>
They accused the management of Michelin of only caring about
the shareholders and caring nothing about the labor force.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist mayor of Clermont-Ferrand, Serge Godard, said
that his city has lost 10,000 jobs because of layoffs by Michelin
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
The unions will organize a protest rally on September 21 in
Clermont-Ferrand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
