<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Loosens Restrictions on Overseas-Funded Investment Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China has loosened restrictions
on the business scope of overseas-funded investment companies, a
senior Chinese official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded investment companies now will be allowed to
sell products made by their plants in China, provide
transportation and storage services to their subsidiaries, and
export products made in China that are not covered by export
quotas and licenses, said Ma Xiuhong, Assistant Minister of the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, at the ongoing
Third China Fair for International Investment and Trade.
</P>
<P>
"This decision aims to enlarge the business scope of investment
companies and help them move toward operating in accord with
international practices," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Ma expressed hope that this move will not affect the main
function of these companies, which is investment.
</P>
<P>
China began to experiment with opening overseas-funded
investment companies at the beginning of the 1990s, and so far has
approved about 200 such companies, with combined investments of 18
billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
