<HEADLINE> Russia Insists on Observance of ABM Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Georgy Mamedov told his U.S. counterpart, Strobe Talbott, Thursday
that Moscow insists on "the strict observance of the cornerstone
agreements" on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum issued by the Russian Foreign Ministry did not
specify which particular "cornerstone agreements" are meant, but
the Interfax news agency said it conveys Russia's opposition to U.
S. plans to alter the Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty (ABM).
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, during the consultations held
Wednesday and Thursday, "the sides discussed the most important
aspects of the Russian-American agenda" on the basis of the
agreements reached by the Russian and U.S. presidents in Cologne
in June 1999, and by the Russian foreign minister and the U.S.
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
"Special emphasis was laid on the problems of disarmament,"
the document says.
</P>
<P>
The next round of consultations on security and disarmament is
to be held in Washington, the Foreign Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the widely spread media reports
of Russia's alleged high-level corruption and money laundering
through U.S. banks.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who left for New York earlier Thursday, said he had
the impression that Russian leaders are very seriously concerned
about the problem of corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia and the United States must work jointly to
ensure Russia's transformation along the road of democratic
reform, Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
