<HEADLINE> Surging Crowds Recall Late Chairman Mao (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Born to a farmer's family in central China's Hunan Province,
Mao had lofty ambitions, and led the CPC members in overturning
the old system and founding the People's Republic of China. As the
founder of New China, his achievements and thoughts continue to
have a great influence on the Chinese society today.
</P>
<P>
Mao passed away on September 9, 1976. Since then, thousands of
people have journeyed to Beijing to show their respects to this
late leader as if he were a member of their family.
</P>
<P>
His grandson, Mao Xinyu, wiped tears away saying, " I came here
to see my grandfather twice a year -- his birthday, on November 26,
and today." Mao Xinyu's parents, Mao Anqing and Shao Hua, as well
as other relatives, also came to the hall today.
</P>
<P>
A graduate of the People's University and now a research fellow
with the Party History Center of the CPC Central Committee, Mao
Xinyu respects his grandfather as "a great leader of the Chinese
people, a great Marxist and a great national hero."
</P>
<P>
The Memorial Hall was completed in May 1977 and opened to the
public on September 9, 1977, on the first anniversary of Mao's
death. To date, a total of 120 million overseas and domestic
visitors have viewed Mao's body, and nearly 80 foreign leaders
have come to show their respects.
</P>
<P>
In the first hour after the hall opened this morning, there
were more than 5,000 people waiting to view Mao, according to
officials at the hall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
