<HEADLINE> Surging Crowds Recall Late Chairman Mao (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- About 2,000 people forming a
200-meter-long line gathered in front of the Memorial Hall of
Chairman Mao Zedong in Tiananmen Square here early this morning.
</P>
<P>
They were there to await the reopening of the hall and to
express their feelings for the late Chinese leader, who passed
away 23 years ago today.
</P>
<P>
Dai Yunpeng, standing in the first row of the line, has made it
a habit to recall Mao here for the past ten years. He said," It is
the last time we have the opportunity to show our respect for
Chairman Mao this century. Today is of great significance also
because it is near the 50th birthday of the People's Republic."
</P>
<P>
The oldest man in the line, Zhao Jingchang from central China's
Henan Province, had something wrong with his leg but persisted in
waiting in front of the hall. His son said, "To be in the presence
of Chairman Mao is a long-cherished dream of my father."
</P>
<P>
Zhao was wearing his best clothes for the occasion as he said,
"I will see Chairman Mao in a high spirit."
</P>
<P>
The base of the white jade statue of Mao was awash with fresh
flowers shortly after the hall opened at eight-thirty.
</P>
<P>
In a crystal coffin, the remains of the great leader rests
peacefully in flowers, covered with the flag of the Communist
Party of China (CPC). Visitors silently walked around the coffin
to view Mao's face. And often their eyes welled with tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
