<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Has Less Strikes in First Eight Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The labor strikes in the
Philippines fell to 43, or down by 47 percent during the first
eight months of the year, the Department of labor and Employment
disclosed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma, the
National Conciliation and Mediation Board (NCMB) said the actual
labor strikes declared as of August 31, 1999, were lower compared
with the 81 cases during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
NCMB Executive Director Buenaventura Magsalin said the result
also recorded a marked decline in the number of workers who
participated in the organized work-stoppages.
</P>
<P>
Latest NCMB data showed there were only 10,129 workers who
participated in strikes during the period January to August as
against the 28,665 workers who joined the picket lines during the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for the decline are the growing maturity of labor
and management as well as the marked improvement in the
conciliation skills of the NCMB in helping parties resolve
dispute, Magsalin said.
</P>
<P>
Observing that there has been relative peace in the
relationships between management and labor, Magsalin said he is
optimistic this trend will be maintained towards the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NCMB also disclosed it has already slashed its
target of strike-level incidence for 1999 to only 75 cases.
</P>
<P>
Once realized, this year will be recorded as the most peaceful
in the history of industrial relations in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
