<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Drops File on Dutch Fixed Book Price System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Thursday that it has closed an investigation into the system for
fixed book prices in the Netherlands because the system had been
changed and will have no "appreciable effect on trade between the
European Union (EU) Member States".
</P>
<P>
The EU executive Commission said its anti-trust regulators have
conducted the probe into the effect of the fixed book price system
over the last year. But concerned parties had made certain changes
to their agreement.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, they abolished resale price maintenance for
foreign books. A possible effect on EU-wide trade has been
alleviated since the system no longer contains provisions
restrictive of competition in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
But the Commission said it will continue to watch closely the
impact of the system on EU-wide trade and will consider re-opening
the case if the factual or legal situation changes.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive would take action if the Dutch system still
has the effect of restricting imports of books or creates any
other such entry barrier or handicap. In monitoring the market,
special attention will be given to the sales of books over the
Internet, the Commission added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
