<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Introduce Technology Using Powerline to Access Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will introduce a
state-of-the-art technology using power line instead of telephone
line to access Internet in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will the first country in Asia to implement the system
which originated from Britain and is currently being tried in
Europe, according to a senior official of Fibrecomm Network (M)
Sdn Bhd which brought in the system.
</P>
<P>
The technology, called Digital Powerline (DPL), utilizes low
voltage power lines and is capable of transmitting Internet at a
speed of up to 1 Mbps or 10 times the current mode, Fibrecomm
General Manage Megat Hisham Hassan said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike the conventional method, this technology does not
require any dial-up. So in places where there are no telephone
lines but have power lines, customers can still access Internet,"
Megat was quoted by Bernama news agency as saying after a function
here.
</P>
<P>
He said that the company had invested 3 million ringgit (0.789
million U.S. dollars) to conduct feasibility studies and trials
which began early this year and are expected to end by June next
year.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, we can provide this technology commercially in July
next year if the trials are successful," he said.
</P>
<P>
Megat said under the system, end users need to have a
communication module connected to the power line and computers.
</P>
<P>
He said that this system offers big potential as telephone
access is not available in every place in the country but most of
them have power lines.
</P>
<P>
There is a four to five million Internet subscriber base in
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
