<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Prime Minister Calls for Healthier Diet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Thursday urged Singaporeans to have healthier diet
besides persevering non-smoking and physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of the National Healthy Lifestyle
Campaign 1999 and the Singapore Helping Employees Achieve
Life-Time Health Award presentation ceremony, Goh said, "I urge
all lovers of good food - in other words, all true Singaporeans to
support these efforts (for healthier diet)."
</P>
<P>
"With a healthier diet, we can live longer to enjoy the
excellent range of food in Singapore," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the prime minister, Singapore's 1998 national
health survey showed that after seven years of efforts the
percentage of Singaporeans who exercise regularly has risen from
13.6 percent in 1992 to 16.8 percent in 1998 while the proportion
of smokers has dropped from 18.3 percent to 15 percent in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
He said the survey also found Singaporeans are now more aware
of the need for a healthy diet and nearly 45 percent of
Singaporeans now make conscious effort to consume less fatty food,
sugar and red meat compared to 28 percent in a similar survey in
1993.
</P>
<P>
But he pointed out that the survey also showed that the rates
of high blood pressure and high blood cholesterol have increased
over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Citing the survey's finding that a high proportion of the
working population still eat out at hawker centers and workplace
canteens, Goh said this underlines the need for foodstall
operators to serve healthier dishes.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the efforts by the Singapore Ministry of Health
(MOH) to influence cooking practices not just in the homes but
also in the 140 hawker centers and over 80 eating establishments
throughout Singapore including best-known restaurants, Goh said,
"We have to press on with our healthy lifestyle campaign." He
urged MOH to extend its health promotion efforts to the work
place.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also announced the formation of a Tripartite
Committee that will take health promotion at the workplace to a
higher plane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
