<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Building Materials Industry More Open to Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China will open wider for
foreign investment in the building materials industry and expects
to make major progress in this sector, a senior Chinese official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Lei Qianzhi, vice director of the State Administration of
Building Materials Industry, said that China has formulated its
investment guidelines for foreign investors according to the
requirements of the development of China's domestic building-
materials market to ensure that foreign investors obtain optimum
returns on their investments.
</P>
<P>
At a symposium here on the building-materials market at the
Third China Fair for International Investment and Trade, Lei said
that foreign funds are welcomed for investment in restructuring
outmoded enterprises to speed up reform of traditional industries
such as cement, glass, and natural stone.
</P>
<P>
Overseas funds are encouraged for high-tech industries, new
building materials, processed products of non-metal materials,
inorganic non-metal materials, building-materials equipment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is especially sought for central and western
China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds can also become involved in property
reorganization projects such as purchasing and merging building-
materials enterprises, replenishing the working capitals of
enterprises, and paying debts for these enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is offering national treatment to foreign-invested
building-material enterprises and improving the provision of quick
and convenient services to foreign business people investing in
building materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, China has approved 9,500 direct overseas-funded
enterprises with contracted investment of 18 billion U.S. dollars
and actual investment of 7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Holderbank, Saint-Gobain, Lafarge, Boluo, Pilkington, Taiheiyo
Cement Co., Daewoo, American Standard, Toto and other established
international building-materials groups have cooperated with their
Chinese counterparts or independently set up solely funded
enterprises in the country.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo (Shandong) Cement Co. Ltd., Shanghai Yaohua Pilkington
Glass Co. Ltd., and Qingyuan Huamei Sanitary Ware Co. Ltd. all
have become pillars in China's cement, glass and ceramic sectors,
and have achieved good economic returns on their investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
