<HEADLINE> SOE Capital Entry Boosts Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Stock Index of
China's two stock exchanges surged by a hefty 7 percent today,
boosted by the good news that state enterprises now are allowed
access to the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Stock Index for the Shanghai Stock Exchange
opened 19.12 points higher than yesterday, and steadily climbed to
close at 1,675.12 points this afternoon, with the total trading
reaching 16 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Component Stock Index for the Shenzhen Stock Exchange shot
up 255.12 points, with total turnover standing at 12.86 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The rally came amid the news that China's state-owned
enterprises now are allowed to invest their capital in China's two
exchanges beginning today. The China Securities Regulatory
Commission, the watchdog of the nation's securities industry, made
the announcement yesterday.
</P>
<P>
There has been a spate of good news for China's stock markets
so far this year, including approval for major securities firms to
expand their capital base, a reduction of the stamp tax on B-share
trading, a major cut in the interest rate, and a levy on bank
interest.
</P>
<P>
After the strong market rally on May 19, the composite index
for the Shanghai and Shenzhen exchanges rose 580 points and 2,040
points, respectively, within a month, and then went into a period
of adjustment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
