<HEADLINE> Toll Rises, Cause Unclear in Moscow Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The number of people killed in
a powerful explosion that ripped through an apartment building has
risen to 21 by Thursday as rescue efforts continue at the site
where some 140 people are feared still trapped under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are trying to establish the cause of the tragedy,
which was earlier believed to be a gas explosion.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo said that law enforcement
agencies are working in several possibilities, adding that the
explosion may have been caused by a bomb planted by terrorists,
although no sign of any explosive device was found in the building
yet.
</P>
<P>
"Specialists must be given time to make a conclusion on the
causes of the explosion," the Interfax news agency quoted him as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Those injured in the blast in the nine-storey building in
Gurianova Street, numbering 73, are being treated in seven
hospitals across the capital city. Most of them suffered burns.
</P>
<P>
A total of 152 people have been rescued from under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
The blast occurred in Moscow's Pechatniki district around
midnight Thursday. Two sections of the six-section building
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
A fire that flared up immediately after the blast was put out
two hours later. Heavy smoke has hampered rescue efforts that
involved about 900 people and 200 pieces of special equipment,
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
About 1,200 people were evacuated from the ruined building and
from a neighboring apartment house, which was also damaged.
</P>
<P>
According to Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, there were 192
apartments in the ruined building, accommodating 648 registered
tenants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
