<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Provides More Opportunities for Job-Seekers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year is
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China. The past five decades of economic achievement has attracted
the attention of the world. Xinhua began issuing a series of
stories on the nation's economy on August 17. This is the 19th in
the series.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS)
show that in the past 50 years the number of employed people in
China's cities grew by nearly thirteen-fold, and the unemployment
rate decreased to 3.1 percent last year from 23.6 percent in 1949.
</P>
<P>
"This is an outstanding achievement for such a developing and
populous country as China," said a senior NBS official.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China had an employed urban population of more than
200 million, a staggering increase from the 15 million of 50 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Most economists agree that rapid economic development of China
over the past several decades not only created more jobs, but also
now provides job-seekers more choices.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises were considered the best places to work
20 years ago, but this is changing as non-state firms are becoming
more appealing to those now entering the job market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Provides More Opportunities for Job-Seekers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, there are nearly
100,000 private firms, which in the past four years have absorbed
180,000 employees laid off by state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The past 20 years saw the number of employed people rise
rapidly, as the private sector was given the green light to
develop, said the NBS.
</P>
<P>
As reforms change the country's economy and employment
structure, so people's ways of thinking are changing.
</P>
<P>
High salaries and the freedom to show one's competence have
become the major standards for more and more people when they seek
employment. Some are even leaving their former stable and
comfortable jobs in state-owned units to try the more competitive
world of private and foreign-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, more than 78 million people were employed by private
firms, according to the NBS.
</P>
<P>
Stiff competition and the development of education in the
country also is producing higher-quality employees. Last year, one-
half of all employees in China had at least a high school
education.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, economists warn that the baby boom of the 1960s
and 1970s is a major reason for the current employment boom, while
the reform of state-owned enterprises has created a surplus of
workers in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is aware of this, and has been taking
steps to solve the problem. A complete network of social security
has been established, with more than 80 million people joining the
basic pension system, and nearly 80 million now covered by
unemployment insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
