<HEADLINE> Jiang Sees Closer Ties Between China, NSW </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese
President Jiang Zemin said Thursday that the deeply-rooted China-
Australia friendship offers good opportunities for further
cooperation between New South Wales (NSW) state and its Chinese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
In a toast at the welcoming dinner hosted by NSW Premier Bob
Carr, President Jiang said that people in Australia have great
interest in developing relations with China and placed high hopes
on China-Australia relationship in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"Our friendship, which is deeply rooted in the hearts of our
two peoples, holds out broad prospects for future growth" of
further cooperation between NSW and its Chinese counterparts, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely wish to work with people from all walks of life
in New South Wales to promote our friendly relations and
cooperation," Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the friendship between NSW and different parts in
China, Jiang said that the state has established and developed
extensive contacts with many Chinese provinces and cities in
recent years,
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jiang went on to say, bilateral exchanges and
cooperation have expanded into the political, economic, trade,
scientific, technological, cultural, educational and tourism
fields and produced gratifying results.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his appreciation for the efforts by Premier
Carr and other state government officials to promote the friendly
exchanges and cooperation between NSW and its Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Carr, on his part, expressed his warm welcome to President
Jiang at the dinner.
</P>
<P>
He hoped to strengthen ties between NSW and China, which has
been sound over years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he congratulated China on the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, President Jiang attended a luncheon hosted
in his honor by Australian Prime Minister John Howard, state
premiers and chief ministers of territories and met NSW Governor
Gordon Samuels.
</P>
<P>
He exchanged views with them on how to further develop
exchanges and cooperation between local governments of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is here on the third leg of his state visit to
Australia, will leave for Cairns on Friday, from where he will
leave for New Zealand to attend the seventh Informal Meeting of
Leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC). 
</P>
