<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound, Dollar Falls in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo
Thursday following the announcement of an unexpected rise in Japan
's gross domestic product (GDP) for the April-June quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 36.18 points, or 0.21
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 17,677.56.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, increased 5.05 points or 0.34 percent to 1,
507.62.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Economic Planning Agency said before the market opened
that Japan's GDP grew a real 0.2 percent in the second quarter
from the previous one, marking its second straight quarterly rise.
</P>
<P>
Japan's private economic institutions had predicted a slight
contraction in the GDP.
</P>
<P>
After hitting the day's high of 17,859.71 in early morning
trading, the key Nikkei index lost its upward momentum, as the yen
's upturn against the U.S. dollar, stirred by the strong GDP data,
made investors hesitant to buy stocks further, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to 473.99 million shares,
slightly down from 484.62 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
NEC Corp. was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers led gainers
586 to 564 despite the overall gain in Nikkei index, with 185
issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar fell to the 108
yen level, pressured by heavy selling after the release of the GDP
data.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 108.82-85 yen, down from
109.60-63 yen at 9 a.m., and from 111.05-15 yen in New York
overnight. It was traded at 111.20-24 yen in Tokyo late Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
