<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Civilian Nuclear Sector Developing Fast  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, construction of the second and third phases of
Qinshan and the Ling'ao and Lianyungang nuclear power stations are
all in full swing.
</P>
<P>
By early next century, China's nuclear-power generating
capacity is expected to reach 9.2 million kilowatts and, by then,
earnings from sales of nuclear power are expected to reach 30
billion yuan a year. The industrial structure of the country's
nuclear industry will be further improved at that point, coupled
with an improved economy and superior technology.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the provinces of Shandong, Fujian, Hainan, Jiangxi,
and Hunan have all been actively preparing for the creation of
their own nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
Experts here expect significant nuclear power development in
China in the next century. By the year 2010, the country's nuclear
power generating capacity will reach 20 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
And by 2020, this capacity should reach 40 million kilowatts,
and the proportion of nuclear power in the country's total power
production should increase to five percent from the existing one
percent, the CNIC experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
