<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Civilian Nuclear Sector Developing Fast (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's nuclear industry is
becoming a new powerhouse of the national economy and has
completed a strategic shift from military production to civilian
application through 20 years of restructuring and readjustment.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear industry is now operating under a new system
featuring a combination of military and civilian production, and
the development of nuclear power in a diversified economy,
according to the China Nuclear Industry Corp (CNIC).
</P>
<P>
The nuclear sector has established a large number of enterprise
groups over the past few years in the more economically developed
coastal areas such as the Municipality of Shanghai and the
provinces of Guangdong and Zhejiang, and has so far developed more
than 1,500 kinds of product for civil use.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear industry has been expanding in China by maintaining
a high growth rate for years, resulting in remarkable improvement
in the country's comprehensive economic strength.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output of civil products now makes up over 80
percent of China's nuclear industrial output.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station in east China's Zhejiang
Province and the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station in south China's
Guangdong Province have been operating smoothly and safely, with
their combined annual power output tripling that of China's total
power output in 1952.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
