<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Agree to Resume Talks on WTO: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, NEW ZEALAND, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China and the
United States have agreed to resume negotiations on China's entry
into the World Trade Organization (WTO), Chinese Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with U.S. trade
representative Charlene Barshefsky, Shi said the U.S. side
proposed through many channels recently that the two countries
resume negotiations on China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
In particular, U.S. President Bill Clinton has formally
proposed to Chinese President Jiang Zemin several times that the
negotiations be resumed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Proceeding from the general prospects for maintaining the
development of Sino-U.S. relations, China agrees that the WTO
negotiations be resumed," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Describing his talks with Barshefsky as "constructive," Shi
said that he and Barshefsky discussed issues relating to the
resumption of the WTO negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, the two sides once again affirmed the importance
of China's entry into the WTO, and agreed to make joint efforts
for realizing this goal as early as possible, according to the
Chinese minister.
</P>
<P>
Shi is in Auckland to attend the two-day ministerial meeting of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum that opened
Thursday in preparation for the 7th informal meeting of APEC
leaders on September 12-13.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Shi also held talks with Russian Trade
Minister Mikhail Fradkov on issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
