<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Experts: 9999 Bug Probably No Bite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The world won't crash Thursday
when international clocks roll over to September 9, 1999,
according to computer experts.
</P>
<P>
Most of the technology experts agree that the 9999 bug will not
bite although the roots of the possible problem are the same as
for the Y2K issue, Canada's Globe and Mail newspaper said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nicknamed "the 9999 glitch", the problem, coming out of the
shortcuts taken by an earlier generation of computer programmers,
is considered the last dress rehearsal before the Y2k bug hits the
world on January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Joe Boivin, an Ottawa expert who runs a Web site devoted to the
Y2K issue, dismisses the possibility of any heavy 9999 shutdown,
saying "it is not likely to generate any significant Y2K problem."
</P>
<P>
"The 9999 code is fairly obvious to find and to fix," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most major institutions have taken some care to ensure smooth
sailing for September 9, 1999, the newspaper continued, adding
that the Royal Bank of Canada began investigating the issue a year
ago and has come to the conclusion: Its computer systems are safe.
</P>
<P>
Experts, however, do not rule out a slim chance that computers,
especially those still working with old COBOL or FORTRAN software,
may misread all those nines as permission to stop everything in
its tracks.
</P>
<P>
As a precaution, Independent Electricity Market Operator of
Canada is sending hundreds of employees into the field to watch
over generation and transmission stations that are usually
unstaffed, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 years ago, many programmers inserted "9999" to
indicate the end of a file or data transfer, unwittingly leaving a
"time bomb" to later developers, who are pulling together today to
ensure a safe transition into the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
