<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Asset Management Corp. Takes over 9 Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's National Asset
Management Corporation (Danaharta) Thursday announced the
appointment of Special Administrators to take over the
administration of 9 companies in the country with immediate
effect.
</P>
<P>
The companies are Advance Synergy Furniture, Austral
Amalgamated, Instangreen Corporation, SPJ Construction,
Instangreen (Landscape), MEC Industrial Park, Perusahaan Sadur
Timah Malaysia, Seng Hup Corporation and Sportma Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Among the 9 companies, three -- Austral Amalgamated,
Instangreen Corporation and Perusahaan Sadur Timah Malaysia -- are
listed on the main board of the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
(KLSE), and two -- Seng Hup and Sportma Corporation-- are listed
on the Second Board of the KLSE.
</P>
<P>
The Special Administrators assume control of the assets and
affairs of the companies, effective Thursday, Danaharta said in a
statement here.
</P>
<P>
The powers of the management and the Board of the companies are
effectively suspended and only the Special Administrators can deal
with the assets of the companies, Danaharta said.
</P>
<P>
In order to preserve the assets of the companies until the
Special Administrators are able to complete their tasks, a
12-month moratorium will take effect from the date of appointment,
Danaharta said, adding during that period, no creditor may take
action against the companies.
</P>
<P>
The Special Administrators will make proposals which would be
examined by independent advisors, and if approved by Danaharta,
the Special Administrators will call for a meeting of secured
creditors to consider and vote on the proposal.
</P>
<P>
A majority in value of secured creditors present and voting at
the meeting must approve the proposal before it can be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Danaharta was specially set up last year to deal with assets of
the financial institutions and companies which faced troubles as a
result of the Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
