<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Claims Fully Committed to IPR Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong claimed Thursday
that its customs was fully committed to intellectual property
rights (IPR) protection and will keep maintaining Hong Kong as a
pirate-free zone.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon of the Hong Kong General Chamber of
Commerce, John Tsang Chun-wah, commissioner of Hong Kong Customs
and Excise, said the territory was no longer a haven for
counterfeit goods.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy to tell you that we have blinded the pirate in
the remaining eye. The piracy situation is now under control,"
said Tsang.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that since last September, customs officers had
cracked 11 underground CD factories and seized 18 production lines
worth some 100 million HK dollars (12.82 million U.S dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tsang noted that up to the end of August about 750 shops had
been raided, over 600 people arrested, and two million pirated
products seized in a mere two months' time.
</P>
<P>
"To these pirates Hong Kong has not been the haven they thought
it was. In the past couple of months it has been plain hell,"
Tsang added.
</P>
<P>
However Tsang said public demand for counterfeit goods would
continue to fuel production, and that the city was aiming to bring
in stiffer jail terms and fines to keep the pirates at bay.
</P>
</TEXT>
