<HEADLINE> Pakistan Seeks Damages From India for Downing Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is considering
various options for seeking damages and compensation from India
for shooting down a Pakistani Navy aircraft last month.
</P>
<P>
A final decision in this regard would be taken next week,
Minister for Law and Justice Khalid Anwar said during his talks
with the media here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan can approach the international court of justice for
recovering the loss, which was caused due to "unlawful and
unprovoked" Indian aggression against the unarmed Pakistani
aircraft, killing 16 persons on board, said Anwar.
</P>
<P>
"Many options are before us to take appropriate action for
seeking justice," he added. Pakistan has demanded 60.2 million
U.S. dollars from New Delhi as compensation.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has also lodged a complaint with the United Nations
over the downing of the navy aircraft. Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz addressed a letter to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
calling the Indian action "an act of military aggression."
</P>
<P>
Aziz had asked Annan to send a fact-finding mission to Pakistan
to investigate the incident. He said that the shooting-down of the
Pakistani plane soon after the Kargil crisis in Kashmir had
further increased tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said apart from taking up the matter with the world court
of justice, Pakistan can consider other options for seeking
justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
