<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM to Attend U.N. Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
will visit New York this month as leader of the Bangladeshi
delegation to the 54th session of the United Nations General
Assembly which is scheduled to start on September 14.
</P>
<P>
This would be the prime minister's second visit to the United
Nations as the head of the Bangladeshi delegation, Foreign
Minister Abdus Samad Azad told reporters Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Hasina led the Bangladeshi delegation to the 51st U.N. General
Assembly in 1996 after taking office.
</P>
<P>
"The 54th U.N. General Assembly is of special significance to
Bangladesh as it marks the silver jubilee of our membership to the
United Nations," Azad said. Bangladesh became a full member of the
United Nations on September 17, 1974, when the General Assembly
adopted a resolution approving the country's admission.
</P>
<P>
Hasina, who would leave for New York next Tuesday leading a
51-member delegation, is expected to address the General Assembly
session on September 20 laying "emphasis on peace and development,
the need for greater international cooperation to address poverty
and socio-economic development, advancement of women,"
highlighting "the concerns of the Least Developed Countries," and
calling "for South-South cooperation, and strengthening of the
United Nations," according to the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
She would hand over a gift to the U.N. secretary general on
behalf of the Bangladeshi government and people, and meet the
secretary general and the president of the 54th U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Hasina would also address an investors' forum and attend
celebrations marking the country's 25th anniversary of U.N.
membership, Azad said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister would leave New York for Paris on September
21 where she would receive the UNESCO peace prize and meet French
President Jacques Chirac before coming back home, the foreign
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
