<HEADLINE> Jiang's Inscription for National Library of China Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The unveiling ceremony for the
inscription written by President Jiang Zemin for the National
Library of China (NLC) was held here today.
</P>
<P>
Undraping the stone carved with Jiang's calligraphy, Li Peng,
chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC), said that the 90-year-old library "has been
transformed from a traditional library into a modern one."
</P>
<P>
Li encouraged the National Library to promote reform and focus
on computerization to cope with an ever-changing society, and
called on governments at all levels to be fully aware of the role
of libraries in social development, and to support their
modernization.
</P>
<P>
The NLC has made a great contribution in inheriting and
developing traditional Chinese culture and spreading modern
science and civilization, and has come to be "a lifetime classroom
for public education." he added.
</P>
<P>
The NLC is the largest in Asia in terms of both space and
number of volumes, and is China's treasury of knowledge and
information.
</P>
<P>
Today marks the 90th anniversary of the founding of the
National Library. Its predecessor, the Beijing Library, was
founded in 1909 and renamed the National Beiping Library in 1928.
After the founding of the People's Republic, it was renamed the
Beijing Library, and last December was renamed the National
Library of China on approval of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
A commemoration meeting was held after the ceremony, and the
library's director, Ren Jiyu, awarded special consultant
certificates to 10 accomplished Chinese scholars from both at home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The NLC plans to advance automation and network creation and
speed up the pace of digitalization, the director pledged, adding
that it will also promote international exchanges and cooperation
to provide information resources accessible to all.  
</P>
</TEXT>
