(UAE) 100 companies and the other for Saudi industries, the Arabic
newspaper Alam Al Yom reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, a Tripoli international fair will be organized on
April 5-20 next year.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Portugal has initiated a credit line of 10 million
euro (10.5 million U.S. dollars) for Moroccan companies,
encouraging them to import Portuguese goods or to participate in
joint ventures with Portuguese companies.
</P>
<P>
The official Moroccan news agency reported Thursday that an
agreement to this effect has been signed in the Moroccan city of
Tangiers during the joint Moroccan-Portuguese supreme committee
meeting.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- UAE banking and economic circles are expecting the
revival of national economy, estimating a 5 percent growth rate in
the gross domestic product this year, the Alam Al Yom said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A 15 percent growth rate in the petroleum sector is also
anticipated thanks to the higher oil prices, bringing in some 42
billion UAE dirhams (11.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the current petroleum prices stand at 15-16
dollars per barrel with a daily production of 2 million barrels
while last year's average oil prices were registered at 12 dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The council of executive managers of the Saudi
Islamic Development Bank has endorsed a new financial credit of 59
million dollars for Islamic member states and Islamic communities
of non-member countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the chairman of the bank Ahmed Mohamed Ali said that
the council Wednesday also decided to provide 300 million dollars
to quake-hit Turkey for rehabilitation, the Alam Al Yom reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The chairman also said a credit of 119.5 million dollars has
been approved to finance eight development projects in member
states.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- During his visit next week to Aden, Yemeni President
Ali Abdullah Saleh will officially inaugurate a free trade zone
that has been in operation for five months, the Arabic daily Al
Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Deputy President of the Free Zones Authority
and Chairman of Aden zone Dirham Abdu Noman, the first part of the
zone that was put into operation last March includes two docks for
container ships.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni President will inspect field activities in the new
containers' port which has cost over 267 million dollars. 
</P>
