<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sutra-Engraved Stones Returned Underground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,082 pieces of ancient
stone engraved with Buddhist sutras today were returned to a
remodeled, climate-controlled version of their original
underground home outside of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Cultural Relics Administration held a ceremony in
honor of the opening of the new facility, located near the Yunju
Temple in Fangshan County. Guests from Japan, the Republic of
Korea, and Taiwan, and Macao attended.
</P>
<P>
The renovated underground showplace, with a construction area
of nearly 400 sq. meters, includes an exhibition room surrounded
by corridors and a computerized control center. Visitors will now
be able to view the stone sutras through a glass wall. Most of the
stone tablets have been arranged in their original positions.
</P>
<P>
Jia Lanpo, Chinese archeologist and academician of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, said that he was pleased with the renovation.
</P>
<P>
Buddhist monks from the Sui Dynasty (581-618) to the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644) originally carved 14,278 stone tablets which
were kept in the caves. In 1957, 10,082 tablets were excavated
from caves, and later stored in a warehouse.
</P>
<P>
The city government decided to re-house the relics because they
were eroding.
</P>
<P>
After the close of today's ceremony, Mei Ninghua, director of
the Beijing Municipal Cultural Relics Administration, solicited
advice on the preservation of the remaining 4,000 stone tablets
still in the Shijing Mountain Sutras Cave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Celebrations to Be Held for Macao's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Macao residents will have hosts
of celebrations around December 20 this year to mark the region's
return to the motherland, a principal organizer said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
From December 19 to 22, Macao people will hold five major
festivities, said Ng Si Meng, director of an organizing committee
in charge of celebration activities. The committee comprises 902
members from all walks of life in Macao.
</P>
<P>
On the night of December 19, the residents will have artistic
performances and gatherings at nine public places. On the
following day, over 10,000 people will take part in a parade that
will be accompanied by lion dancing, dragon dancing and
performances presented by grassroots social bodies.
</P>
<P>
An artistic evening party will be held on the night of December
20 with the participation of more than 1,300 performers under the
auspices of China's Ministry of Culture and artistic organizations
in Macao.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of the handover, some 10,000 Macao people
will give performances at an open stadium. It is estimated that
the number of audience may reach 40,000.
</P>
<P>
Another evening party will also be staged on December 22, which
will be participated by local artistic social bodies, according to
Ng Si Meng.
</P>
<P>
"People of various social quarters in Macao have shown great
enthusiasm about the region's upcoming return to the motherland,"
he said, adding that local residents have donated more than 13
million patacas (1.63 million U.S. dollars) since the committee
was set up on March 27.
</P>
<P>
The committee expected to receive 10 million patacas (1.25
million dollars) to fund the expenses of celebration activities. "
In addition to donating money, many residents give up their spare
time and take an active part in relevant rehearsals," Ng said.
</P>
<P>
With abundant funds, the committee plans to produce two types
of commemorative envelopes to be issued on October 31, which is
the first day of the 50-day countdown to Macao's return, and on
December 20, Ng Si Meng said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
