<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislative Market Reform Pressing Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong SAR government
is progressing in full steam on its legislative reform in a drive
to strengthen Hong Kong's position in the rapidly changing
international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of legislative reform is to provide a modern
and flexible regulatory framework for the securities and futures
markets, said a government spokesman Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Legislative Council will start a series of
meetings Friday with representatives from the Financial Services
Bureau (FSB) and the Securities and Futures Commission (SFC) to
discuss the new proposals at its Sub-committee on Securities and
Futures Bill, the FSB spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus on the review of licensing regime for
market intermediaries, introduction of more proportionate
disciplinary sanctions, and establishment of the Securities and
Futures Appeals Tribunal, the FSB spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Under the streamlined licensing regime proposed in the bill,
intermediaries will only be required to apply for a single license
for conducting regulated activities in different markets and
products. This will reduce the cost of compliance and hence
regulatory burden on the intermediaries, he said.
</P>
<P>
As an effort to strengthen the supervision of intermediaries,
the bill will introduce intermediate sanctions which are more
proportionate to the gravity of the misconduct, without causing
undue harm to innocent parties like the intermediary's clients and
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
To provide for additional checks and balances, a statutory
Securities and Futures Appeals Tribunal is proposed to be
established. The Tribunal will be chaired by a High Court Judge
and include a number of market practitioners of high standing.
</P>
<P>
Other major proposals scheduled for discussion at following
meetings are establishment of the Market Misconduct Tribunal,
enhancing Securities and Futures Commission's inquiry powers into
listed companies, and disclosure of interests in securities, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The new framework will be on a par with international
standards to facilitate our competition in the increasingly
globalized market. We are pressing ahead with an aim to introduce
the bill into LegCo by the end of the year," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
