<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks Church's Support in Anti-corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo has called upon the church to join in the anti-corruption
crusade in the west African country, The Guardian newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The church cannot be indifferent to the corruption of its
members. It cannot stand by and do nothing when some of its
members live above their means while others grovel in poverty,"
the president said through his Minister of Justice Kanu Agabi
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo is in Libya attending a special summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Representing the president, Agabi said at the second plenary of
the Catholic Bishops Conference of Nigeria in the northern city of
Jos that the clerics have a duty to challenge and question church
members who live above their means.
</P>
<P>
"The failure of the nation is the failure of the church and
that the failure of the citizen is the failure of the church," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the church "to go after those who are lost to
drugs, who are lost to crime, who are lost to corruption and other
forms of immorality. "
</P>
<P>
Noting that the constitution recognizes and guarantees freedom
of conscience and religion, he said the adherents of such
religions are also " citizens of one country."
</P>
<P>
The president advised them to imbibe the virtue of forgiveness
which is one of the cardinal pillars of their faith, instead of
looking upon the privileges of any religion as confined or
restricted to any tribe, race or generation.
</P>
<P>
The church leaders were also urged to restrain their members
from the kind of ethnic carnage that was witnessed recently in
Shagamu and Kano, while appealing for calm and patience in the
Niger Delta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
