<HEADLINE> Athens Quake Death Toll Climbs to 72 As Rescue Work Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Tuesday's
devastating earthquake in the Greek capital of Athens rose to 72
Thursday as Greek and foreign rescue teams continued their work in
the rubble of collapsed buildings in the quake-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Officials believe that the death toll could rise to 90 or 100.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 rescue teams, including those from Turkey, France,
Germany, Switzerland, Ukraine and Israel, are making efforts to
dig out persons still buried in debris in 13 worst-hit locations.
</P>
<P>
They have so far managed to pull 86 persons alive out of the
rubble of collapsed houses and factories, but more than 50 persons
are still missing.
</P>
<P>
An Austrian rescue team is expected to arrive in Athens later
Thursday to assist operations.
</P>
<P>
Besides the relief measures announced on Wednesday by Greek
Prime Minister Costas Simitis, engineers have already inspected
more than 3,000 buildings and houses in the stricken northwestern
Athens, of which about 45 percent are considered inhabitable, 41
percent reparable, and 14 percent will have to be demolished.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake measuring 5.9 on the Richter scale rocked Athens
Tuesday afternoon with its epicenter in the Mount Parnitha region,
some 20 kilometers northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greece is the sixth most seismically active country in the
world, with earthquakes occurring in the country on an average
rate of once in every five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
