<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Pledges to Restore Order in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie said here Thursday that his government will make every
effort to restore security and order in violence-torn East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The president made the pledge when meeting with a U.N. Security
Council team at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia has asked the international community, especially
the United Nations to give an opportunity to Indonesia for the
return of security and order there (East Timor)," Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas, who accompanying the president during the meeting,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The five-member U.N. mission arrived here Wednesday to exchange
views with the Indonesian government on the latest developments in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the question of sending peace-keeping forces to
East Timor, Alatas said there are two obstacles which should be
cleared for the sending of the peace-keeping forces. Firstly, he
said, the making of the decision will cost a long time because
countries which want to send forces should be appointed and who
will finance the action. Secondly, Indonesia is till responsible
for the security in East Timor in accordance with an agreement
signed by the U.N., Indonesia and Portugal in May this year.
</P>
<P>
And meanwhile, he said, East Timor is still part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In the August 30 direct autonomy ballot, 78.5 percent of East
Timorese voters cast their votes for independence, instead of
wide-ranging autonomy proposed by the Indonesian government in
January this year.
</P>
<P>
But, clashes between pro-integration and pro-independence
groups have taken place in East Timor since the announcement of
the ballot results on September 4. Reports said dozens of people
have been killed and more than 100,000 people have fled to nearby
provinces of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian military declared a state of emergency in East
Timor on Tuesday morning in a bid to control the violence. The
period of the emergency will last till the situation returns to
normal.
</P>
<P>
Alatas was optimistic that the security situation in East Timor
could soon return to normal as there was no burning and shooting
in the past 24 hours there. So, he held that until now there is no
need for sending peace-keeping forces from foreign countries to
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
However, Alatas said, the president told the U.N. mission that
Indonesia is ready to accept humanitarian aid for the East
Timorese refugees.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. mission will hold talks with Defense Minister
and Armed Forces chief Wiranto on Friday morning. The delegation
will ask for a visit to East Timor. Alatas predicted that the
delegation could go to Dili, capital of East Timor, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move has never been recognized by the
United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa Launches CD-ROM on Mandela's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A multimedia CD on the
life of former South African president Nelson Mandela was
officially launched by the Nelson Mandela Children's Fund
Wednesday in Midrand, north of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The CD-ROM, which contains video clips, slide shows,
photographs and written language, is the first of its kind ever
released. It contains unique historical and biographical material
of Mandela, some of which has never been published before.
</P>
<P>
It is divided into different sections devoted to different
aspects and stages of Mandela's almost legendary life, including
his personal life, his vigorous struggle against apartheid, his
life in jail, his release and the first democratic election with
him as the first black president of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zindzi Mandela-Hlongwane, one of Mandela's daughters, said at
the launch: "Even though the life of Nelson Mandela has been well
documented in books, photographs and film, it has been interesting
for me, as his daughter, to have been able to see all this
information gathered in one place."
</P>
<P>
The CD, entitled "Nelson Mandela -- the Symbol of a Nation",
was produced by the Nelson Mandela Children's Fund and will be
distributed throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Since its founding in 1994, the fund has distributed more than
36 million rand (six million U.S. dollars) through 983 projects in
communities throughout South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is the founder and chairperson of the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
