<HEADLINE> Cambodia Holds Seminar on Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A two-day anti-drug
national seminar began here Thursday to discuss ways to timely and
effectively reduce and prevent increasing drug abuse in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from government sectors, police, provinces, the
United Nations and other international organizations are attending
the meeting organized by United Nations International Drug Control
Program and the National Authority for Combating Drugs of
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"Drugs are ravaging the Cambodian society especially among the
youths and are becoming major barriers to the development of the
country," a government official told the National Seminar on Drug
Abuse Prevention and Drug Demand Reduction.
</P>
<P>
"The elimination of drug abuses is the removal of the roots of
human trafficking and exploitation and social anarchy," the
official added.
</P>
<P>
The seminar aims to bring together key authorities,
international and local agencies and other professionals with
strong interest in drug abuse prevention and demand reduction
issues and make recommendations for promoting drug abuse
prevention and drug demand reduction in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"Today's Cambodia is not only a transit country for drugs but
also a place of selling and use. Many people working near the Thai
border have died from over-use of amphetamines," according to Uk
Vithun, Minister of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Amphetamines were increasingly common in border provinces such
as Koh Kong, Battambang and Banteay Meanchey, Uk Vithun added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting called on the government and authorities to enhance
drug education among the youths and families, to take strict
actions and sufficient procedures to prevent the influx of drugs
and to crack down and educate drug abusers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
