<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two-thirds of Ethiopians at Risk of Malaria: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 40 million
Ethiopians, or two- thirds of the country's 60-million population,
are threatened by malaria, one of major killer diseases in
country, the Monitor newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Malaria often attacks after the main rainy season which falls
between September and November. Usually, up to five million are
infected with the disease every year, according to the Health
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the ministry have advised people to pour burned
engine oil or kerosene to swamps and ponds to kill malaria carrier
-- mosquitos and their eggs.
</P>
<P>
The burned out engine oil and kerosene will have no major
ecological effect, said Daniel Kebede, who is working for the
ministry's malaria control unit.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government has pledged about 10 million U.S.
dollars for the malaria control program in 1999/2000 fiscal year,
up from last year's budget of about four million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The annual National Malaria Social Mobilization Week was
observed from August 24 to 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
The government-sponsored campaign was designed to further
bolster the participation of governmental and non-governmental
organizations as well as the public at large in the fight against
the infective disease.
</P>
<P>
Although capital Addis Ababa is regarded as a malaria free
zone, people living in parts of the city, such as near the Bole
International Airport, are also at risk of malaria, medical
workers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Launches First Portrait Currency Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Thursday launched
its first portrait currency notes in history -- the Presidential
Notes - as part of the national millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Commissioners of Currency of Singapore (BCCS)
introduced the entire new series of currency notes at the opening
of the Currency 21 - Presidential Notes Exhibition which was
officiated by Singapore Minister for Finance Richard Hu.
</P>
<P>
The newly-introduced portrait series, featuring the portrait of
Singapore's first President Inche Yousof bin Ishak on the front of
all new notes, includes all seven denomination notes respectively
in value of 2, 5, 10, 50, 100, 1,000 and 10,000 Singapore dollars
and incorporates a host of security features which combine the
most up-to-date security devices and design elements with modern
print technology.
</P>
<P>
After the issuance of the portrait series, the currently
circulated notes, including the Ship Series notes, as well as the
Orchid and Bird Series notes will remain legal tender and will
continue to be used side-by-side with the portrait series.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Richard Hu noted that the Portrait Notes contain
many "firsts" -- the first time in the history of Singapore that
the central theme of the notes features a portrait instead of
flowers, birds and ships, the first time that all seven
denominations are released together, the first time that a
Singapore currency series is designed entirely by a Singaporean.
</P>
<P>
He added that the faith and confidence that people have in
their currency is very much dependent on how secure the notes are
protected against counterfeiting. Hu said the BCCS has
incorporated many "first time" security features into the portrait
notes, which are state-of-the-art devices to combat
counterfeiting, in particular those employing reprographics
technology such as color copiers and computer scanners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
