<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes Measures to Protect Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government will
adopt a package of strong measures to protect industrial property
rights, Vietnam's business newspaper The Saigon Times Daily
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The measures were proposed in view of rapidly growing disputes
on industrial property rights in Vietnam in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Trade will seek ways to further manage the use
of technology, materials and brand-names, and to better monitor
quality as well as brand-name and industrial design registration.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will keep a close watch on markets to prevent the
trading of imitations, and will issue lists of quality goods and
registered brand names.
</P>
<P>
The sources of the ministry said that police and market
monitoring forces would coordinate to fight against the production
and trading of counterfeit goods and those found violating the
regulations would be seriously punished.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese and foreign individuals and organizations annually
submitted some 10,000 applications for industrial property rights
protection, said an official of the Industrial Property
Department.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam, the official said, has so far issued 89,453 protection
certificates, with 1,200 for inventions and useful solutions,
5,244 for industrial designs and 83,000 for brand names. Of these,
Ho Chi Minh City accounts for 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the certificates are for food, beverages,
pharmaceuticals and cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
According to police and market monitoring forces of the
country, 565 infringement cases were brought to court from 1995 to
1998, with 1,024 people found guilty of producing and storing
imitation goods.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Vietnamese police uncovered 102
cases of producing or trading of imitations, mostly in such
sectors as food, cosmetics, garments, footwear and electronic
appliances.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
