<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elf Sinks 6th Oil Well in Angolan Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Elf Exploration Angola has
discovered another oil well in the productive east Atlantic Ocean
near Angola, the Jornal de Angola newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new oil well called "Orquidea-1" was found in the "Block
17" which has a great reserve of crude oil and is located some 200
kilometers northwest to Luanda, the capital of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Workers for the Elf Angola, an affiliated company of the French
Elf Aquitaine, sank the well in the earth crust 1,197 meters below
sea level.
</P>
<P>
Orquidea-1 is the sixth oil well found by Elf in the Block 17,
which is abundant in oil reserves and therefore, profitable.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996 when Elf became the operator of the block, the
company has successively found six productive oil wells,
respectively denominated as Girassol, Dalia, Rosa, Lirio, Tulipa
and Orquidea.
</P>
<P>
Among them, the explored oil reserves of Girassol and Dalia are
660 million and 700 million barrels while Rosa and Lirio produce
12,000 and 11000 barrels per day respectively.
</P>
<P>
Elf, as the operator of the block, invested a lot in the oil
exploration in the Block 17, accounting for 35 percent of the
total investment in the block by foreign companies including Esso
Exploration Angola, BP Exploration Angola Ltd., Den Norske Stats
Oljeseskap A.S, Norsk Hydro Asa and Fina Exploration MB, BV.
</P>
<P>
Only after Nigeria, Angola is the second largest oil-producing
country in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The southern African country has divided its seas into blocks
and foreign companies have to compete with each other for the
authorization of exploration by the Angolan government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
