<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Demands Pinochet's Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Belgium has joined Spain,
France and Switzerland in demanding the extradition of former
Chilean president Gen. Augusto Pinochet for alleged torture
against Belgian citizens during his rule of Chile beginning in the
1970s, a Spanish court said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish National Court said the International Police (
Interpol) has informed it of the extradition request of a Belgian
procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, is under 24-hour guard at a house southwest of
London since his arrest by British police on October 16 last year
when he went to London to treat illness. His arrest was requested
by Spanish magistrate Baltasar Garzon, who wants to try the former
Chilean leader for various alleged crimes committed during his
rule.
</P>
<P>
In line with Garzon's charges, the Spanish government demanded
that the British government hand over Pinochet for trials in Spain.
France and Switzerland followed suit, requiring the extradition of
Pinochet on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
But Chile is strongly opposed to these extradition requests,
maintaining that such efforts would undermine its sovereignty. The
Chilean government has asked these countries to allow Pinochet to
return home.
</P>
<P>
After failing to solve the Pinochet issue through diplomatic
channels, the Chilean government decided to seek an international
arbitrage.
</P>
<P>
Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes has said that Spain would
elaborate on its stance on the issue in the days to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
