<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman GDP to Grow by 2.4 Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Omani official has
predicted the country's Gross Domestic Product will grow by 2.4
percent in 1999 thanks to higher oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices in the world market have exceeded Oman government's
projections and therefore, the prospect for the country's economy
has tangibly improved, said Mohammed Bin Nasser Al Khusaibi,
secretary-general of the Omani National Economy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent upswing in oil prices has reflected
positively on Oman's economy, allowing a re-balancing of the
general financial situation, the Dubai-based Khaleej Times
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He expected a noticeable drop in the budget deficit in view of
the price hikes. Nearly 70 percent of the Oman government's
revenues come from oil export.
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed the continuation of the current situation
depends on oil producers' commitment to production cuts and
improvement in world economy.
</P>
<P>
Oman's real budget deficit swelled to 975 million U.S dollars
in 1998 from a 766 million dollars forecast.
</P>
<P>
In January, Oman issued its 1999 budget, forecasting revenues
at 3.96 billion dollars and spending at 5.6 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
