<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Needs $30 Bln to Revive Economy, Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) - Nigerian economy needs about 30
billion U. S. dollars every year in the coming five years to
revive, diversify and significantly reduce its heavy dependence on
imports.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Dotun Philips, a renowned economist in the west African
country, said in Lagos Wednesday that for best, "crude oil trade
will probably produce only about 10 billion dollars out of this
requirement, leaving an annual resource gap of about 20 billion
dollars."
</P>
<P>
The professor told the Nigerian-American Chamber of Commerce
that ordinarily, the gap ought to "be filled mainly through
international flows from non-crude oil trade, international trade,
investment and loans."
</P>
<P>
But the international flows "have for long proved insignificant
and elusive and are most likely to remain so," The Guardian
newspaper Thursday quoted the economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country's non-oil exports have never yielded
up to 500 million dollars in any given year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the declining international aid from donor
countries, unattractiveness to foreign investors and huge external
debt, Philips said that the federal government needs to devote far
much more effort to significantly revamping and improving the
internal conditions of the country.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, yearly foreign direct investment in
Nigeria had hardly exceeded 1.5 billion dollars while portfolio
investment was most insignificant "with only a 50.5-million-dollar
inflow through the Nigerian Stock Exchange in 1998, the highest
volume ever."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of external debt, Philips said the country should
not expect any debt relief in the foreseeable future as Nigeria is
perceived as a rich country which, but for mismanagement, "can and
should fully repay its external debt".
</P>
<P>
He also urged the government to beef up its efforts to chase
elusive debt relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
