<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Media Seeks to Avoid Covering News on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's National Audiovisual
Media Council has organized a meeting with the country's major
media to discuss means to avoid covering events attended or
sponsored by Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held Wednesday, was attended by representatives of
the country's all audiovisual media, including seven TV stations
and five radio stations, the Daily Star reported Thursday
</P>
<P>
Council President Nasser Qandil said after the meeting that
"we reached full agreement regarding the caution shown by these
media outlets in their eschewing traps set by Israel."
</P>
<P>
He added that Israeli policy consisted of attempting to cast
doubts on the country's rejection of any form of contact with the
enemy.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is officially at war with Israel which has carved out a
border strip in south Lebanon as security zone.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government prohibits its citizens from contacting
Israel and otherwise they will face the strict penalty, including
the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the council stirred a controversy when it
recommended closing LBCI TV station, one of the most popular TV
stations in the Middle East, for three days after its
correspondent in Jordan covered an event attended by Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
But after the station did not air the report and promised to
take disciplinary action against the correspondent, the cabinet
rejected the recommendation and instead warned stations against
breaking the boycott of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
