<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Favors Settling Trade Disputes Through Consultation: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 9 (Xinhua) - China on Thursday
called on Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) members to
settle their trade disputes through consultation and refrain from
resorting to means like anti-dumping measures and trade sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote speech at the two-day 11th APEC ministerial
meeting which opened here Thursday, Shi Guangsheng, minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation of China, said that
although APEC has made important progress in the area of trade and
investment for the past decade, there still exist in the
Asia-Pacific region various discriminatory barriers to trade.
</P>
<P>
Citing examples like misuse of anti-dumping measures,
quantitative restrictions on products from developing members, and
even trade sanctions or threat of trade sanctions, Shi stressed
that "all these run counter to the APEC spirit of consultation and
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"As we are to embrace the new millennium," he said, "we will
present the new century our best gift if we can reach a consensus
and state that APEC members will settle trade disputes through
consultations, eliminate discriminatory technical barriers,
prevent the misuse of anti-dumping measures and do away with trade
sanctions."
</P>
<P>
As to the Individual Action Plan (IAP) and Collective Action
Plan (CAP) processes, Shi said that China always believes that IAP
is the primary mechanism towards realizing the APEC objective of
trade and investment liberalization.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, experience in the last couple of years also
proves that to push forward the APEC process of trade and
investment liberalization and facilitation through both IAP and
CAP is a workable approach, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the future, APEC should focus its attention on
the implementation of existing CAP while continuing to value the
role of IAP as the main channel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
