<HEADLINE> China's "Silver Hair" Consumer Market Shows Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- More should be done to develop
consumer opportunities for the elderly, as the goods and services
designed for "silver hairs" aren't up to speed with China's
rapidly growing senior population, experts here said today.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar held here for developing consumer goods for the
elderly, the experts pointed out that China's population of people
60 or older has exceeded 120 million and will reach 450 million by
the middle of next century, with one of every four Chinese being
elderly.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that tremendous commercial potential exists for
developing goods for seniors.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenfan of the China National Committee on Aging (CNCA)
said he is optimistic about the industry that caters to China's
elderly, explaining that their numbers are large, they have a
steadily growing income, and they represent various levels of
consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the total sum of retirement pension, re-
employment income and estovers of Chinese seniors will reach 400
billion yuan in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The experts also noted that the some industries clearly haven't
paid enough attention to this commercial opportunity. For example,
Beijing currently has just 300 senior citizen's homes, enough for
only 10,000 people, while the city has 1.7 million elderly.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Shanghai also show that among the city's
citizens who traveled last year, less than five percent were over
65. Seniors there have complained that available travel routes don
't match their habits and interests.
</P>
<P>
The experts called on business people to provide goods and
services that are truly wanted by the elderly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
