<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New WTO Negotiations Should Accommodate Developing Members' Interests: Chinese Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 9 (Xinhua) - The new round of
World Trade Organization (WTO) negotiations scheduled to start
later this year should give full consideration to the requests and
interests of its developing members, a senior Chinese official
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 11th APEC ministerial meeting, Shi Guangsheng,
minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation of China, said
that the negotiations should be more focused on practical,
effective and balanced implementation of various agreements
already reached during the Uruguay Round, particularly those
catering to the needs of developing economies.
</P>
<P>
As to the new agendas, he added, the opinions and suggestions
of all parties, especially those of the vast number of developing
economies should be listened to.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister noted that the requests and interests of
developing economies -- the bulk of WTO membership -- should be
seriously taken into account throughout the negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the day, the results of the negotiations should
help to build a more open and equitable multilateral trading
system and play a more positive role in promoting economic
development of all members, instead of just a few," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Only in this way can the new round of WTO negotiations win
active support and full participation of the large number of
developing economies, effectively push for continuous development
of global trade and economy, improve the welfare of more people
and succeed in real sense, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
As to APEC's possible contributions to the WTO, Shi noted that
APEC has already made important contributions to the multilateral
trading system through its work in the trade and investment fields
in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
He said the forum will make another important contribution to
WTO if it presents a series of constructive proposals and
recommendations on the basis of consensus for the new round of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, he reminded APEC members that contribution to WTO is
only one aspect of APEC's integrated efforts to promote economic
stability and development of its members in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Being a major trading nation and destination of foreign direct
investment in the world, China is closely watching the progress of
the new round of negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a global organization dealing with multilateral trade
relations, the WTO will lack representation and universality
without the participation of large trading nations like China, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed the hope that China could participate in
the new round of negotiations as a full member of WTO so as to
make its due contributions to the development of world trade and
global economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
