<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Papua New Guinean FMs Meet on Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan met here Thursday with his Papua New Guinean
counterpart Michael Somare on relations between their two
countries.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Tang told Somare that China always attaches
great importance to its relations with Papua New Guinea and views
the country as a major cooperation partner in the South Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, relations between the two countries took an
unexpected turn, but the Papua New Guinean government led by Prime
Minister Mekere Morauta swiftly made a wise decision by
reaffirming that the country would continue to pursue the
One-China policy.
</P>
<P>
"China highly appreciates and welcomes this decision, which has
eliminated an obstacle against the further development of
relations between China and Papua New Guinea," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
Facts have proven that the political attempt of the Taiwanese
authorities to lure South Pacific countries with money to develop
so- called official relations with Taiwan will eventually be seen
through by the South Pacific people, the Chinese foreign minister
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese government has always worked for
the development of long-term friendly and mutually beneficial
relations between China and Papua New Guinea, and will continue to
make unswerving efforts for the development of such relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Somare said that Papua New
Guinea pursues the One-China policy, which is not only an
established policy of the Papua New Guinean government, but also a
firm commitment of the Morauta government.
</P>
<P>
He said that presently, relations between China and Papua New
Guinea are well established and that his country will make
continued efforts for further expanding friendly relations of
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Tang also met with Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov to discuss bilateral relations and exchange views on
international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers are in Auckland to attend a ministerial
meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum that
opened earlier Thursday in preparation for the September 12-13 7th
informal meeting of APEC leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
