<HEADLINE> China's Largest Nylon-66 Salt Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's largest nylon-66
salts producer in the city of Pingdingshan in Henan Province is
expected to put an end to China's dependence on nylon-66 salts
imports.
</P>
<P>
The material is used for producing chemical fibers and plastics
and widely used for synthetic fibers used for knitwear, tires, and
in machinery and electric industries.
</P>
<P>
Work on the nylon salts plant began in 1994 and was completed
this March at a cost of 2.68 billion yuan (322 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The plant is equipped with technology from Japan's Asahi
Engineering Co. Ltd. and Italy's Noy Vallesina Engineering S.P.A..
It has a production capacity of 65,000 tons of nylon-66 salts
annually.
</P>
<P>
By July, it had produced 28,000 tons of nylon-66 salts.
</P>
<P>
By using the product, China Shenma Group, the nylon-66 salts
project sponsor, has produced automobile tire cloth and sold it to
domestic and overseas motor works.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Rural Women Illiterate Rate Hits 40% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- About 40 percent of Zambian
rural adult women are illiterate, Zambian Minister of Community
Development Dawson Lupunga has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambian newspaper, The Post, Thursday quoted the minister as
saying that democracy is compromised when the majority in the
country are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
Lupunga said at a function Wednesday marking the International
Literacy Day, that the situation has contributed to social
economic development being impeded because the most productive
people are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
He said despite the government's rigorous campaign for basic
education to every child, especially the girl child, more has to
be done to reduce illiteracy among the most affected people.
</P>
<P>
Lupunga said the current illiteracy rate of 40 percent should
be reduced to 12 percent by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The key to eradicating poverty is political and national with
all the citizens making "each one teach one a reality," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
