<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Y2K-Induced Incidents Reported in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- No Y2K incidents have been
reported so far in Hong Kong, said the Central Coordinating Center
(CCC) for monitoring the computer bug problem during the rollover
to September 9, which is one of the Y2K critical dates, early
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government
and various essential service sectors went on full alert during
the rollover.
</P>
<P>
The CCC, which was activated at 10 p.m. Wednesday, has been set
up to monitor the situation across Hong Kong during the rollover
to 9 September, to coordinate cross-sector emergency responses to
Y2K-induced incidents, as well as to collect, collate and
disseminate information.
</P>
<P>
It is manned by officers from a number of concerned bureaus and
departments, including the Information Technology and Broadcasting
Bureau, Security Bureau, Information Technology Services
Department, Office of the Telecommunications Authority and
Electrical and Mechanical Services Department.
</P>
<P>
To coincide with the activation of the CCC, the 13 sector-wide
coordinating centers covering various essential services have also
come into operation.
</P>
<P>
The sectors are food supply, transport, financial services,
public order, fire and emergency services, environment, aviation,
public health, telecommunication, port management, energy supply,
immigration and broadcasting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Y2K-Induced Incidents Reported in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
These sector-wide centers are responsible for coordinating
emergency responses to Y2K-induced incidents among different
departments/organizations within their respective sectors.
</P>
<P>
They maintain close liaison with the CCC and report to it on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
This monitoring arrangement has been operating smoothly, and so
far no Y2K incidents have been reported, said Jessie Ting, deputy
secretary for information technology and broadcasting who is also
the controller of the CCC.
</P>
<P>
"Both the government and the essential services providers have
made tremendous efforts to solve the Y2K problem. We have also
drawn up contingency arrangements to ensure a prompt response to
any unforeseen Y2K-induced incidents," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The risk that Hong Kong will be adversely affected by the Y2K
problem on the rollover to 9 September is very minimal," Ting said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the experience gained from the operation of the
CCC and the 13 sector-wide coordinating centers on this occasion
would help the government and all concerned to set up an effective
monitoring and coordinating mechanism during the rollover to the
new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
