<HEADLINE> Obuchi, 2 Others File Candidacies for Presidency of Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi and two senior politicians of Japan's ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) filed their candidacies Thursday for the
party's upcoming presidential race, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The two candidates who will vie for a two-year term at the LDP'
s top post with Obuchi are former LDP Secretary General Koichi
Kato and former party policy chief Taku Yamasaki.
</P>
<P>
The winner of the leadership race, which will be held on
September 21, will become Japan's prime minister as the LDP has a
majority in the powerful House of Representatives (lower house).
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, who is serving out the remainder of the term of his
predecessor, Ryutaro Hashimoto, looks certain to win his first
full two-year term since he has support of two-thirds of the party
's 371 lawmakers. His current tenure as LDP leader ends September
30
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to lead in votes to be cast by LDP members
nationwide. A total of 2.91 million party members are eligible to
participate in a mail-in vote, with 10,000 votes equivalent to one
vote by a legislator.
</P>
<P>
Kato and Yamasaki run in the race with the aim to position
themselves as possible successors to Obuchi. Kato leads the party'
s second largest faction with 70 Diet (parliament) members, while
Yamasaki heads a faction with 31 Diet members.
</P>
<P>
One focus of the election campaign is on a plan to expand the
current coalition government between the LDP and the Liberal Party
to include the New Komeito party, Japan's second largest
opposition party. Obuchi's two rivals are critical of the proposed
alliance.
</P>
<P>
Other issues include ways to achieve economic recovery and
whether to revise Japan's constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
