<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes DNA Data Bank for Law Enforcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China has established a DNA
data bank for tracking and identifying criminals, an official from
the Ministry of Justice announced today.
</P>
<P>
The DNA collection program was headed by the Shanghai-based
Institute of Forensic Science under the Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Forensic experts point out that the data bank marks a great
step forward for China's use of technology in criminal
investigation and identification.
</P>
<P>
With the help of computers, police will be able to compare DNA
extracted from hair or blood left at crime scenes with the DNA
information from criminals that has been stored. If the suspect is
a repeat offender, police may solve the case more quickly.
</P>
<P>
The repetition of DNA code in more than one person is
extraordinarily rare. Only twins of the same ovum, or the donor
and benefactor of a marrow transplant, may share similar DNA codes.
</P>
<P>
The ministry official also said that this first DNA data bank
will pave the way for a uniform DNA network throughout China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
