<HEADLINE> Macao's Future Chief Strives for Steady Power Transfer (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Edmund Ho Hau Wah, chief
executive-designate of the Macao Special Administrative Region (
SAR), has pledged that he will go all out to ensure a smooth power
transfer in Macao and the region's better development.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the transfer of power on December 20 this year
are now well under way and the leading officials of the future SAR
have started work, he said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of seven principal officials of the SAR
government and the SAR's procurator-general by China's State
Council has not only paved the way for building the SAR, but also
demonstrated the trust of the central people's government that the
Macao people can administer Macao well, Edmund Ho said.
</P>
<P>
"With this trust, work for Macao's future will definitely go
smoothly and the newly appointed principal officials and I are all
confident about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration, he
said, an increasing number of Macao people began to take leading
positions in the government, legislature and judiciary of Macao,
and they have accumulated relative experience in their work.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he noted that only a few Macao residents of
Chinese origin were able to take senior positions in the Macao
government. The insufficient work experience of the future SAR's
policy-makers will make it difficult in the running of the SAR
government, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
