<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Large-Scale Water Exploration in Ortos Basin (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua)-- The Chinese government is set
to launch a large-scale water-location project in the Ortos Basin
in a bid to hasten development in the country's arid northwest
region.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Land and Resources has decided to readjust
water exploration in the area region and focus its efforts on the
basin of Ortos, sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
From this year to 2002, the ministry is to spend a total of 80
million yuan (about 9.6 million U.S. dollars) on the stock-taking
of underground water resources in the basin, Xinhua has learned.
</P>
<P>
The basin, situated in the east of China's northwest region,
covers 280,000 square kilometers. It extends through parts or the
whole of five provinces and autonomous regions, Shaanxi, Gangsu,
Ningxia, Shanxi and Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The area is rich in coal, oil, natural gas and other natural
resources, and its coal reserves account for over half of China's
total.
</P>
<P>
"It is pivotal to the development of our country's northwest
region," an official from the Ministry of Land and Resources said
of the basin.
</P>
<P>
Its economy is relatively strong compared with other parts of
the region, and its population represents over 60 percent of the
region's total.
</P>
<P>
However, limited precipitation and high rate of evaporation
make it the lowest in the country in terms of per capita water
resources.
</P>
<P>
As a result, "the economic and social development in Ortos has
been seriously handicapped," the official commented.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has decided to enhance exploration in the basin so
as to gain a clearer picture of its underground water resources
and volumes that can be used in the long run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
