<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Large-Scale Water Exploration in Ortos Basin (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the meantime, sections with rich underground water will also
be marked as sites for the future development.
</P>
<P>
"This will have a major impact on the framing and
implementation of our country's overall plans of speeded-up
development in the northwest," the official noted.
</P>
<P>
The Ortos is a sedimentary basin formed in the Mesozoic Era.
Previous explorations have indicated that rich, high-quality water
exists under the surface of the basin.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the basin holds a total of 24.5 billion
cubic meters of underground water a year, of which 16.3 billion
cubic meters can be used.
</P>
<P>
But it's not easy to tap the potentially huge bodies of water
underground, since the basin's structure is quite complicated and
its water distribution systems are still unknown.
</P>
<P>
Only when sections with rich underground water have been
located can there be an economic basis for large-scale pumping up
and development, the experts noted.
</P>
<P>
To speed up water-location in the basin, the ministry convened
a meeting of hydrogeologists from Shaanxi and other northwest
provinces in Yinchuan, capital of the Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, hydrogeologists, along with officials from
the five provinces and regions, reviewed the successes and
failures of water exploration over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
They concluded that more effort should be focused on major
projects, such as the Ortos basin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
