<HEADLINE> Kenya to Enact Anti-Corruption Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive
anti-corruption bill will be enacted in Kenya to deal with the
menace more effectively, Chairman of the Parliamentary Select
Committee on Corruption, Musikari Kombo, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The current bill was defective and narrow and needed to be
rectified to cover more broadly the issue of corruption, Kombo
said in Mombasa, a port city in southeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his committee was formed last year by parliament
to study and investigate the causes, nature, extent and impact of
corruption in the east African country with a view of seeking
remedial measures.
</P>
<P>
The committee's term of reference included identification of
key perpetrators and beneficiaries of corruption and to recommend
immediate effective measure to be taken against such individuals
involved in corruption and recover public property, Kombo said.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times newspaper Thursday quoted the chairman as saying
that his committee is to enact the bill to provide for stiff
penalties on all corruption related offences.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his satisfaction that the majority of Kenyans were
aware of the existence of corruption, saying that for the vice to
be eradicated, all Kenyans must participate in the fight against
it.
</P>
<P>
Due to rampant corruption and poor governance in the country,
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended a loan package
totalling 205 million U.S. dollars to Kenya in July, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
