<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Stresses Economic Cooperation Among APEC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan Thursday called on members of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) to strengthen economic
cooperation and build a favorable macro environment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 11th APEC Ministerial Meeting, which began
Thursday in Auckland, the biggest city of New Zealand, Tang said
that "at this time last year when the Asian financial crisis was
still ravaging the Asia-Pacific region, all of us worried about
the economic prospects of this region. But today we are very much
relieved to see a gratifying momentum for economic recovery
emerging in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"APEC member economies affected by the crisis are gradually
bottoming out and beginning to look up. The foreign exchange and
stock markets in the region are being stabilized.
</P>
<P>
"This is a hard-won situation that has come as a result of both
the vigorous efforts by the crisis-affected members in their
reform and restructuring and the support from the region and the
international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
But, the Chinese foreign minister warned that APEC members
should not be overoptimistic about that at this point as economic
recovery in Asia has just started, the root causes for some
ingrained problems in the crisis-affected economies are yet to be
resolved, the global economic environment is not very stable and
trade protectionism has been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, to strengthen economic cooperation, to build a
favorable macro environment and to reinforce the recovery results
are still an assiduous task confronting all of us," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted the Asian financial crisis has caused great
difficulties to China's economy as well. "Despite the enormous
pressures, the Chinese government has, bearing in mind the greater
interests of this region, adopted necessary measures, overcome
various difficulties and successfully maintained a relatively high
economic growth rate, thus making its due contribution to the
economic recovery in the region."
</P>
<P>
At present, he continued, China's economy is still faced with
such difficulties as slack domestic demand, sluggish investment
and declining export.
</P>
<P>
"In response to these adverse factors, the Chinese government
has decided to further improve all-round macro-control of the
economy and stick to a proactive fiscal and monetary policy to
pull up economic growth. Meanwhile, we will continue to deepen the
reform, open wider to the outside world and step up international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that with our hard work, China will realize a
sustained, rapid and sound development of its economy and
contribute more to the economic recovery and development in Asia,"
Tang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
