<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Set up National Housing Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will set up a national
housing trust and a housing finance bank to relax the country's
housing shortage.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Local Government and National Housing John Nkomo
said, in Harare when presenting a draft housing policy, that
housing should be enshrined in the constitution as a human rights.
</P>
<P>
The trust would finance housing development by both private and
public sectors, monitor and evaluate the performance of the
housing sector and carry out research to give advice to
stake-holders on trends in the sector.
</P>
<P>
It would be supported by the proposed bank, which would act as
a vehicle of mobilizing funds from individual savings and loans,
pension funds and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
The bank would be used as a springboard for private sector
participation in housing development by financing small-scale
developers and contractors.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's housing backlog currently stands at one million
homes and has been failing to meet an annual demand for 250,000
houses and flats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
