<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Annual Inflation Jumps to 6.9% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's overall year-on-year
inflation jumped to 6.9 percent in the 12 months to August fuelled
by a rise in food prices and a depreciating currency, according to
the Central Bank of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Underlying year-on-year inflation, which the central bank
targets at 5 percent or below, climbed to 5.9 percent in August
compared to 4.9 percent in July, the East African Standard
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Assistant chief economist of the central bank, Boniface Masua
said that a sharp increase in food and fuel prices had put heavy
pressure on inflation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the rise in food prices is linked to a shortage
in maize, Kenya's staple food commodity, after poor seasonal long
rains.
</P>
<P>
Masua also attributed the rise in inflation to the fall in the
shilling value over the month. The shilling lost 1.42 percent in
August and had fallen to around 75.76 against the U.S. dollar from
just 61 in January.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that it has been the government's desire to
control the annual inflation rate to single digit level, but sharp
depreciation of the shilling, soaring petroleum prices and surging
interest rates now threaten the set objective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
