<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 06:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Releases 200 Palestinian Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Israel released 200
Palestinian political prisoners early Thursday morning as promised
in a new peace deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under a revised agreement for the Wye Accord signed last Sunday
in Egyptian Red Sea resort Sharm El Sheikh, Israel, among other
things, should let go 350 Palestinian political prisoners in two
phases. The second batch of 150 will get freedom on October 8.
</P>
<P>
The move marked the start of the implementation of the new
agreement, which also calls for Israeli troops withdrawal from
another 11 percent of the West Bank by January 20.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the dawn broke Thursday, the prisoners got on buses
outside Israeli prisons in different places, with their hands
still cuffed. They were dropped off in military checkpoints on the
way to Gaza and the West Bank cities of Ramallah and Hebron.
</P>
<P>
A government committee headed by the director-general of the
Justice Ministry approved the list of the prisoners Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 200 released prisoners, some 150 have the record of
killing Palestinians who had cooperated with Israeli security
services, and 17 others assisted in non-fatal attacks against Jews.
</P>
<P>
Israel has insisted that it not release those who had killed
Israelis or belong to the Islamic militant groups like Hamas and
Jihad.
</P>
<P>
The issue of freeing Palestinian political prisoners had been a
sticking point in Palestinian-Israeli negotiations on the
resumption of the implementation of the Wye Accord signed last
October and suspended two months later.
</P>
<P>
The two sides compromised at last with the mediation of
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, which led to the conclusion of the revised
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The release came one day after Israel's Knesset (parliament)
overwhelmingly approved the agreement Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, the 23-minister cabinet had given go-ahead
to the implementation of first stage troops pullout from 7 percent
of the West Bank as well as the prisoner release. In the vote, 17
pros and 1 con, with one abstention and four absence.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said the decision to hand
over parts of the biblical land of Israel was not easy, but it was
in Israel's best interest to move toward comprehensive peace with
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Israeli negotiator Gilad Sher has said that the first
redeployment will be carried out on September 13, the 6th
anniversary of the signing of the historic Oslo accords, which
kicked off the Mideast peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Capital Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
Kaifeng, in modern day Henan Province, wants to turn the old
capital city into a modern tourist center in 3 years.
</P>
<P>
A new development plan calls for historic sites in the city, in
central China, to be refurbished and modern tourist facilities to
be built. The city is also planning to build a mock-up of the
Kaifeng of the Song Dynasty (10th-13th century), with work to
start later this year.
</P>
<P>
Three major tourist routes linking Kaifeng with other three
scenic spots will also be opened by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Kaifeng has a history of almost 3,000 years and was one of six
old Chinese capitals. The city has had to be rebuilt several times
because of Yellow River floods.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the number of tourists in the
city was up 160 percent and tourism revenues were up 6-fold from
the same period of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
