<HEADLINE> 2 Pro-Israeli Militiamen Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Two members of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanon Army (SLA) were wounded Wednesday night by a
roadside bomb in south Lebanon, the Voice of the People radio
reported Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The two militiamen, one in a serious condition, were hurt when
a roadside bomb blew up their armored car in the Rihan area in the
eastern sector of the Israeli occupied border zone in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the explosion.
</P>
<P>
The blast raised to 48 the number of SLA members wounded in
south Lebanon since the start of this year while another 11 were
killed.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli troops and its
ally SLA out of the country. 
</P>
