<HEADLINE> Development Goals For Southern Chinese Delta And Its Economic Zones Defined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province plans to turn its special economic zones (SEZs) and the
Pearl River Delta into the country's major high-tech industrial
center by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The southern province has three of China's first four special
economic zones, which have enjoyed special preferential policies
to help local economic development.
</P>
<P>
At a recent provincial symposium on opening up the SEZs and the
Pearl River Delta, Guangdong's Provincial Party Secretary Li
Changchun said that an efforts needs to be made to get the SEZs
and the delta area to cooperate more closely with Hong Kong and
Macao and to have closer ties with international markets. They are
required to lead the socialist market economy and be demonstration
areas for sustainable development and modernization, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, provincial and lower-level governments were told to
transform government functions and reform approval procedures to
accelerate the pace of establishing a modern enterprise system and
better management of state assets to build an orderly socialist
market economy.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Party Committee and Provincial People's
Government have decided to form a leading group to coordinate this
SEZ and delta modernization drive and to make certain that the
work will be a success. 
</P>
