<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Happy Lives For China's Kirgiz People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Kirgiz are members of one
of China's 55 ethnic groups, may still be familiar with their 200,
000-line folk epic "Manass", but their lives have undergone
fundamental changes in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
There are 150,000 Kirgiz, 80 percent of them living in the
Kizilsu Kirgiz Autonomous Prefecture in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region. They are one of the ancient nomadic
tribes of northern China and many of them still engage mainly in
animal husbandry and supplement it with farming and dairy products
in the Tianshan Mountains and on the Pamir Plateau.
</P>
<P>
But, at least half of them have left their centuries-old life
of moving from one grazing area to another behind and have built
permanent houses.
</P>
<P>
Their agriculture and animal husbandry have had good results
for 19 years in a row thanks to more modern agricultural
techniques. The prefecture's grain output amounted to 160,000 tons
last year and the annual per-capita income of herdsmen is at least
1,200 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The beautiful scenes and landscapes described in the "Manass"
have become a reality and the vast Gobi has become an immense
forest. The green grass is dotted with sheep and cattle and new
buildings equipped with modern furniture and household appliances
can be seen everywhere.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
