<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's GDP Rises 0.2 Percent in April-June Period in Real Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan's gross domestic product (
GDP) grew 0.2 percent in the April-June period from the previous
quarter in real terms, or an annualized growth of 0.9 percent, the
Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rise marks the second consecutive quarterly increase,
following a revised 2 percent quarter-to-quarter growth or an
annualized expansion of 8.1 percent in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
With the robust second-quarter performance, the agency said,
the Japanese government's target of a 0.5 percent real growth for
the fiscal 1999 is attainable, even if the economy shrinks by 0.5
percent in each of the three remaining quarters of the fiscal year
ending on March 31 next year.
</P>
<P>
The agency attributed the April-June GDP growth primarily to
solid personal consumption, which rose 0.8 percent for the second
consecutive quarterly rise. Personal consumption makes up about 60
percent of Japan's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Another factor was a strong 16.1 percent increase in housing
investment, due to the government's tax cuts for home buyers.
</P>
<P>
Corporate capital spending and public investment, however,
dropped 4 percent from the previous quarter respectively.
</P>
<P>
The domestic-demand component of GDP increased a preliminary 0.
2 percent, while the external-demand component was flat, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the GDP data, EPA chief Taichi Sakaiya said the
Japanese economy is recovering, but added it is too early to feel
at ease over the economy's future.
</P>
<P>
Sakaiya said it is unclear whether the Japanese economy has
bottomed out, but it has recovered from the crisis-like situation.
</P>
<P>
However, Sakaiya said it is premature to relax over the future
course of the economy and the government will take measures to
keep it on a recovery track.
</P>
<P>
GDP measures the value of goods and services produced within a
nation. Real GDP figures are adjusted for inflation and seasonal
variations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
