<HEADLINE> Two Drug-Trafficking Groups Tracked Down in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Two groups engaged in drug
trafficking have been arrested in Poland, said Polish police on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lodz city police arrested 18 drug traffickers belonging to a
ring operating between Poland and the Netherlands, which was
believed to be the largest of its kind along the route.
</P>
<P>
The Polish news agency PAP quoted authorities as saying that
the group transported marijuana into Poland and amphetamine into
the Netherlands for three years. Drug sales by them amounted to 35
million zloty (around 9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ring had a well-organized network in Poland, through which
drugs were sold in bars, universities and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
The arrested could face a sentence of up to 15 years
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
In another case, five youths, including a Dutch, were charged
with drug trafficking and selling in an eastern Polish city. From
them police seized 37 kilograms of drugs, which had a market value
of 240,000 zloty (60,000 dollars). 
</P>
