<HEADLINE> Moscow Apartment Building Blast Toll Rises to 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The number of people killed in
a huge explosion that ripped through an apartment building in
Moscow early Thursday has risen to 13, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 37 wounded were hospitalized while 150 others are believed
to be still under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
The blast, believed to be caused by gas, destroyed 108
apartments in the building on Guryanova Street at 00:12 local time
(20:12 GMT Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
The explosion killed two people immediately. Four bodies have
been recovered from the debris.
</P>
<P>
Sixty ambulance teams, rescuers and 40 fire-fighting crews were
working at the scene. They had rescued 18 people alive from the
rubble as of 04:00 (00:00 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has been informed of the
explosion and the country's interior and emergency affairs
ministers were at the scene, Tass quoted government spokesman
Igor Shchyogolev as saying.
</P>
<P>
"A criminal case has been instituted on the fact of the
explosion and investigation has started," Shchyogolev said.
</P>
<P>
Forty residents of the building have been evacuated and
accommodated in the Tula cinema, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately clear whether the explosion was
accidental or set off intentionally.
</P>
<P>
On August 31, a bomb went off in a mall under Moscow's Manezh
Square near the Kremlin, injuring 44 people. One of the victims, a
25-year-old Russian woman, died last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The woman and her Lebanese husband in their honeymoon were near
the mall's video game arcade, where an estimated equivalent of 300
grams of TNT went off. Her husband, with burns of over 70 percent
of his body surface, remains in critical condition in the
Sklifosofsky Institute of Intensive Care, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Police are still investigating the explosion, and Islamic
militants related to the breakaway republic of Chechnya were seen
as one of the possible perpetuators of the attack.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement officers also discovered leaflets claimed to be
authored by an anti-consumerism group that hails "city guerrilla
warfare" aimed at creating a "revolutionary situation" in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In Russia's southern Dagestan republic, a huge car bomb last
Saturday demolished a five-story residential building inside a
military compound, killing over 60 people and wounding 50.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militants were thought to be behind the blast, which
also badly damaged two nearby buildings and smashed windows
throughout the complex.
</P>
<P>
A second bomb in another car was found and defused Sunday in
the military housing complex. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
