<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Companies Lag in Business Skills Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite the economic crisis,
Thai companies still lack sense of urgency to improve the business
skills of their employees, The Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It will likely take at least two to three years for Thai
companies to catch up to the standards of their counterparts in
this respect in Singapore and Malaysia, the newspaper quoted the
Thai branch of American Management Association (AMA) as saying.
</P>
<P>
AMA, the third largest training and development agency in the
United States, said that Thai firms, especially family-owned
groups, have been paying poor attention to the development of
their employees' skills.
</P>
<P>
To date, only the Thai branches of multinational companies and
Thai firms which have been partly taken over by foreign firms are
attentive to this issue, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The business skills of an average Thai company employee is
three to five years behind those of a Singaporean, working in the
same position, and two or three years behind a Malaysian, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
