<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-U.S. Summit to Improve Relations: Chinese FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming
meeting between the Chinese and United States presidents will be
of great significance to the improvement of Sino-U.S. relations,
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting over breakfast with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Tang said that more
significantly, the summit meeting will have important and
far-reaching influence on the development of trans-century
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his U.S. counterpart Bill
Clinton will meet on the sidelines of the 7th informal meeting of
leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum
scheduled for September 12-13 in Auckland.
</P>
<P>
Both Tang and Albright are in Auckland attending the two-day
APEC ministerial meeting that opened Thursday in preparation for
the informal meeting of APEC leaders.
</P>
<P>
Describing his meeting with Albright as "candid, useful and
significant," Tang recalled that the exchange of visit between
Chinese and U.S. heads of state and Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's
visit to the United States in April served as a momentum and
opportunity for the development and improvement of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
But a series of ensuing developments, particularly the May 7
U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia, "have worsened
Sino- U.S. relations, and the responsibility lies entirely on the
U.S. side," he said.
</P>
<P>
Presently, Sino-U.S. relations are in a crucial stage, with
both challenges and opportunities. As two influential powers in
the world, China and the United States both shoulder important and
common responsibilities for maintaining peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region and the world as a whole, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
"So, we hope that the U.S. side will take concrete actions to
eliminate obstacles to the restoration, improvement and
development of Sino-U.S. relations," he urged.
</P>
<P>
Whether Sino-U.S. relations can continue to be improved depends
on whether the U.S. side can create favorable conditions for the
improvement of relations by taking concrete actions and steps,
Tang stressed.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Taiwan, Tang said that Lee Teng-hui, leader of
the Taiwan authorities, is going farther and farther on his way of
seeking "independence of Taiwan" by dishing out his "two-states"
theory, damaging the stability of the Taiwan Strait, worsening and
straining relations across the Taiwan Strait and threatening the
peace and stability of the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister stressed that as the issue of
Taiwan concerns China's sovereignty and territorial integrity, the
Chinese people will never allow any attempt of splitting the
motherland to succeed.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that the U.S. side, proceeding from the overall
situation of Sino-U.S. relations and abiding by with concrete
actions the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques and relevant
commitments it has made, stop making any statement and taking any
act that could encourage Lee Teng-hui's arrogance in selling his
'two-states' theory, explicitly oppose Lee Teng-hui's statement
and acts of splitting China, reduce and finally stop the sale of
weapons to Taiwan, and not provide Taiwan with the Theater Missile
Defense system, relevant techniques, equipment and auxiliary
systems," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that "the question of Taiwan is the most sensitive,
most salient and most important issue in Sino-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that the United States should have a clear
recognition of the serious nature of this question and the
possible harm it could bring to Sino-U.S. relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that Lee Teng-hui is the biggest troublemaker, the
biggest obstacle and the biggest stumbling block in the way of
development of Sino- U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Albright said that through efforts by the
governments of both countries, there have been some improvements
in U.S.-China relations and that President Clinton expects to once
again meet with President Jiang Zemin to have friendly, frank and
important discussions on bilateral relations and other issues of
common concern.
</P>
<P>
The United States hopes that relations between the two
countries will be fully restored and develop as quickly as
possible in the fundamental interest of the two countries,
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
The United States will continue to pursue its one-China policy
and abide by the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
