<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Designates City For Culture of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to designate the eastern harbor town of Trincomalee as a
"City for a Culture of Peace" from September 14 to coincide with
the International Day of Peace, media sources here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO has proposed that Sri Lanka promotes Trincomalee
city as a "City of Peace" and the Sri Lankan government has
accepted the proposal, the sources said, adding a ceremony will be
organized on September 14 to celebrate the International Day of
Peace in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
It is intended to symbolize hope and progress, triumph over
violence and the meeting of cultures, civilizations and religions,
a UNESCO official here was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Trincomalee has been selected as it is a city representing the
major ethnic groups in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Sri Lanka National Commission for
UNESCO Dr. Premadasa Udagama has called on all Sri Lankans to take
a pledge on September 14 to respect life, reject violence, share
with others, listen to understand, preserve the planet and
rediscover solidarity to mark the day.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education and Higher Education has also called
on all schools to mark the day as an International Peace Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
