<HEADLINE> Bangkok Airways Expects Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok Airways expects annual
revenue to grow by 20 percent over the next five years with sales
totaling five billion baht (131.6 million U.S. dollars) in 2004.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Thursday quoted Bangkok Airways President
Prasert Prasartthongosoth as saying that the airline will not join
any fare-cutting war.
</P>
<P>
The president said Bangkok Airways just wants to be a small
regional airline which offers "reasonable fares".
</P>
<P>
Thailand has four airlines at present, which are Thai Airways
International, Bangkok Airways, PB Air and Angel Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Ranking second among the four, Bangkok Airways has forecast 2.4
billion baht (63.5 million dollars) in total sales revenue this
year, up 18 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
It expects to generate three billion baht (78.9 million
dollars) next year and five billion baht (131.6 million dollars)
in 2004.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the airline said it plans to open new international
routes between Thailand and neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Flights are planned between Samui island, a famous resort in
southern Thailand, and Langkawi and Kuala Lumpur in Malaysia, and
Medan in Indonesia, and a connection from Singapore to Indonesia's
Bali.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by the International Air Transport
Association, tourist arrivals in Indochina between 2000 and 2009
will reach 200 million, of which 70 percent will be Asian
visitors. 
</P>
