<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Likely to Be Site of U.S. Missile Defense System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
Wednesday it has selected the state of Alaska as the most likely
site for its proposed anti-ballistic missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
The announcement, which was made by U.S. State Department
spokesman James Rubin, came as U.S. and Russian officials started
negotiations in Moscow Wednesday on the terms under which a
missile defense could be established.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the former Soviet Union agreed in the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty not to construct a national
defense system against such missiles. The theory is that leaving
both sides vulnerable would deter nuclear attacks because both
countries would face deadly retaliation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott Wednesday opened
a two-day talk with Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Georgy Mamedov
on reducing nuclear stockpiles and possible changes of the treaty.
U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen is also scheduled to visit
Moscow next Monday for talks with Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev on the issue. Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin is
expected to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton in New Zealand next
week.
</P>
<P>
Russia, financially hard pressed to create its own anti-missile
defense, strongly opposes making major changes to the Cold War-era
treaty. It said that an anti-missile defense system in the United
States would tilt the strategic balance and start a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the Clinton administration won't decide whether to
deploy a national missile defense system until next summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Revs Up Research in Controlled Nuclear Fusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's research in controlled
nuclear fusion is to enter a new stage with the operation of
another nuclear fusion experimental device -- Tokamak HL-2A, which
is being built on the outskirts of Chengdu, the capital city of
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Controlled thermonuclear fusion is thought to be a major energy
source for the future. Unlike fission, which leaves a large amount
of highly radioactive waste, fusion is similar to what happens
when the sun produces light and heat.
</P>
<P>
Tokamak HL-2A was a major overseas cooperation project using
equipment from Germany at the China National Nuclear Corporation's
Southwest Physics Research Institute, China's first and biggest
nuclear fusion experiment center.
</P>
<P>
China started work on controlled nuclear fusion in the 1950s
and developed the Tokamak HL-1 by its own efforts and put it into
operation at the institute in 1984, leading to improvements in
recent years. In 1994, a new system from a modified HL-1
installation was put into use for greater efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Despite the world recognized research results gained with the
help of existing equipment, Chinese researchers of controlled
nuclear fusion decided to build the more advanced Tokamak HL-2A
facility with German equipment, aiming to enhance their role in
the "sphere of nuclear fusion".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
