<HEADLINE> Davenport, Williams Reach U.S. Open Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Lindsay
Davenport of the United States got a little help from rival Mary
Pierce of France Wednesday to advance into the semifinals of the U.
S. Open.
</P>
<P>
After Pierce squandered two match points in the 10th game of
the third set, rain forced a stoppage of play for just over an
hour. When play resumed, Davenport capitalized on her second match
point when Pierce committed her seventh double fault. Davenport
escaped with a 6-2, 3-6, 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
The second-seeded Davenport, who extended her U.S. Open winning
streak to 12 matches, will face No. 7 Serena Williams after
Williams rallied for a 4-6, 6-3, 6-2 victory over fourth seed
Monica Seles Wednesday night in an all-American quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
On the men's side, second seed Andre Agassi of the United
States looks to continue his impressive run through the draw
tonight when he won the first set 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
If Agassi win through, he will take on third seed Yevgeny
Kafelnikov of Russia, who blew a two-set lead but withstood a
record-breaking performance to beat No. 12 Richard Krajicek of the
Netherlands 7-6 (7-0), 7-6 (7-4), 3-6, 1-6, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
Davenport broke Pierce four times and fired nine aces as she
improved to 23-3 in her last 26 matches. She is seeking her second
Grand Slam of the year after winning Wimbledon on July 4.
</P>
<P>
"I've had a good time trying to defend this title, whether it
ends Friday or Saturday," Davenport said. "Pulling out a match
like this makes it probably even more special than just winning 6-
3,6-3."
</P>
<P>
Pierce, the fifth seed, committed 44 unforced errors as she
failed in a bid to reach her first U.S. Open semifinal.
</P>
<P>
Agassi has emerged as the favorite to win his second U.S. Open
title after the early withdrawal of top seed Pete Sampras. Ranked
as low as 141st in the world a year ago, Agassi vaulted to No. 1
in July, thanks to winning the French Open and reaching the
Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
Williams, who joins older sister Venus in the semifinals, began
the match much the same way she did in the third round Monday by
dropping the first set.
</P>
<P>
But Williams, who recorded five aces in each set, opened the
second with a break and led 4-1. Seles broke in the seventh game,
but Williams broke back for a 5-3 advantage.
</P>
<P>
Seles committed 33 unforced errors against 21 winners, losing
for only the fifth time in 48 U.S. Open matches. A two-time U.S.
Open champion, Seles fell to 0-3 lifetime against Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
