<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Case Affects Tourism in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tourism in Chile has fallen
by 15 percent so far this year since the detention of former
Chilean military leader Augusto Pinochet in London, said
authorities on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of European visitors to Chile has been reduced
substantially, especially those from Spain and Britain, said the
director of the National Service for Tourism, Cesar Gomez.
</P>
<P>
Gomez attributed the reduction of British and Spanish tourists
to advice given by their governments and also by some European
travel agents.
</P>
<P>
He added that eventually those potential European tourists who
are planning to visit Chile will forget about the Pinochet case.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was detained on October 16 last year in London on the
request of Spanish courts probing killings of Spanish citizens
between 1973 and 1990 in Chile when Pinochet ran the country.
</P>
<P>
Though Pinochet has denied the charges, Britain is scheduled to
begin extradition proceedings on September 27. 
</P>
