<HEADLINE> Myanmar Absorbs 5.6B Dollars Foreign Investment in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar brought in a total of
5.641 billion U.S. dollars' foreign investment in 219 projects
from 22 countries and regions between April 1994 and April 1999,
according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figures provided by Myanmar's Central Statistical
Organization show that of the total foreign investment absorbed
during the five-year period, the sum coming from member countries
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) totaled
2.966 billion dollars in 106 projects.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN investment amount and projects accounted for 52.58
percent and 48.4 percent of the total respectively.
</P>
<P>
Singapore ranked first in the line-up of investment from ASEAN
member countries with 1.087 billion dollars, followed by Thailand
with 961.2 million dollars and Malaysia with 533.4 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of foreign investment to Myanmar sharply decreased
as a result of the Asian financial crisis which broke out in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
During the period from July 1997 to April this year, Myanmar
drew in a total of 619 million dollars' foreign investment, of
which that from ASEAN member countries stood at 406 million
dollars, accounting for 65.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
Since adopting the open-door economic policy in late 1988,
Myanmar has obtained a total of 7.1 billion dollars' foreign
investment which came from 24 countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
