<HEADLINE> OAS Backs Chile's Stand on Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of American
States (OAS) backed the position taken by the Chilean government
on the Pinochet case, Secretary General of OAS Cesar Gaviria said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Whatever crime a Chilean citizen has committed in Chile, it
comes under the jurisdiction of that country, Gaviria said in an
interview published in the Spanish newspaper "El Pais" Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the action of the Spanish Judge Baltazar Garzon who
ordered the detention of former Chilean military leader Augusto
Pinochet provokes judicial uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
"Personally, I believe the stand the Chilean government is
defending" is correct, added Gaviria.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean government said the arrest of Pinochet in London
last October at the request of the Spanish judge was an extra-
territorial action.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Spanish Judge Garzon ordered 83-year-old Pinochet to
present himself in court in person to hear charges of human rights
abuses, including the disappearance of political opponents during
his military rule in 1973-1990.
</P>
<P>
Chile said that Pinochet should be allowed to return to his
country to stand trial there and also proposed that the Pinochet
case should be taken to international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the detention of Pinochet, Chilean President
Eduardo Frei canceled his presence at the Ibero-American Summit in
Havana in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
