<HEADLINE> Aging in Latin America Imposes New Challenges: CEPAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The aging of the Latin
American population will be one of the central themes of a meeting
which began Wednesday, said executive secretary of the Economic
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (CEPAL) Jose
Antonio Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
Between the years 2000 and 2025, the population of people aged
60 and above will double, reaching 14 percent of the total
population.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2050, it is expected that one in four of the Latin
American and Caribbean population will fall within this group,
while in the year 2025, the population of elderly adults will
surpass that of children under the age of fifteen in six countries.
</P>
<P>
The change in the composition of ages will be the object of
analysis at this meeting, said Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the forum will discuss the health of the
elderly, and the challenges which aging imposes on the societies
of the region, as well as the social economics of the adult
population.
</P>
<P>
We are united in a common interest to achieve advances in
society for all ages in this International Year of Elderly People.
said Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
This meeting was organized by CEPAL, the U.N. Population Fund
and the Pan-American Health Organizations.
</P>
<P>
Around 300 representatives and experts from governments, civil
society and international organizations are attending the meeting,
which will end on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
