<HEADLINE> Hungary, Yugoslavia Team up to Resume Railway Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Hungary and Yugoslavia will
team up to resume railroad transport as soon as possible, the two
countries' railroad authorities announced Wednesday here at their
first meeting since NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
Svetolik Knostadinovic, director general of the Yugoslav
Railroad Bureau, informed the Hungarians that NATO bombed his
country's railway infrastructure more than 300 times during the 78-
day air attack, causing a damage of billions of dollars to the
rails, bridges and communication systems.
</P>
<P>
At present, Yugoslavia is doing its best to put the railway
back into service and resume connection with other countries, said
Knostadinovic.
</P>
<P>
Kukey Marton, director general of the Hungarian national
railroad company, noted that resuming bilateral railway transport
accords with the interest of both countries.
</P>
<P>
He offered aid to the rebuilding of Yugoslavia's wrecked works
and to its efforts in restoring railroad connections with other
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
A working group will discuss the details of cooperation next
month. 
</P>
