<HEADLINE> CAW Chooses Ford Motor as Target of Contract Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Auto Workers (CAW)
has chosen Ford Motor Co. Wednesday as the target of its first
contract negotiations to be launched this fall.
</P>
<P>
Buzz Hargrove, president of CAW, the country's biggest workers
union, also announced that September 21 midnight will be the
deadline of strike, which has happened to Ford three times since
1970.
</P>
<P>
About 49,000 union workers will be involved in the upcoming
negotiations with the Big Three automakers when their current
three-year contracts expire on September 21.
</P>
<P>
The unions concentrate on talks with one company until an
agreement is reached. That contract then sets the pattern for
deals with the other two companies.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the UAW is still trying to decide whether
General Motors Corp. or DaimlerChrysler AG would be the first
company to negotiate with.
</P>
<P>
Ford Canada is producing some of the U.S. automaker's best
selling vehicles at a time when the North American market is
setting sales records, the media said.
</P>
<P>
But Ford company officials are reported to take the workers'
demand for better pay as tough to satisfy because of the hefty
costs. 
