<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paper Industry Faces Challenges From Electronic Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The electronic information
revolution spells change, but not doom, for the world's paper
producers, according to a study on five markets released by a
global management consulting firm Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Boston Consulting Group's study provides an analysis of the
impact of electronic media on paper use over the next five years,
and identifies key factors that are driving information sources to
substitute digital distribution for physical distribution of data.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, the pulp and paper industry, long
plagued by over-capacity and slowness to react, faces increased
challenges as the electronic screen replaces the printed page. But
opportunities remain in many areas of the business.
</P>
<P>
The consulting firm investigated paper consumption through the
year 2003 in the United States, Germany, Britain, France and Japan,
which comprise more than half the global graphic paper market.
Seven major applications, namely newspapers, magazines, catalogs,
books, direct mail, directories and office papers, were considered
in the study.
</P>
<P>
Overall, according to the study, worldwide consumption of paper
will continue to increase, with growth in most sectors offsetting
losses resulting from the switch to electronic media.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of cut-size office paper will double from 1996
levels by 2003, because of the increase in individual printing by
office and home printers.
</P>
<P>
Newsprint will be the biggest loser. About 15 percent of 1997
North American capacity will be superfluous by 2003, and for Japan,
about five percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, the considerable information content of
most newspapers -- combined with high fixed cost and a
subsidization of content by advertising -- makes them particularly
vulnerable to both indirect and direct electronic substitution.
For the typical newspaper, which garners more than two-thirds of
its income from advertising, this indirect substitution will
trigger a loss of crucial income.
</P>
<P>
Classified advertisements, the biggest single revenue source
for newspapers, are already beginning to shift to online formats.
Online advertising revenues grew 240 percent in 1997 and 112
percent in 1998 in those markets. The study predicts that by 2003
about 15 percent of the U.S. classified market will be online; 10
percent each in the other four markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
