<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storm Kills 10 in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 people were
killed and 4,000 others injured by the Hurricane "Greg" in Mexico,
the authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Even though the phenomenon had converted into a tropical storm,
the authorities were maintaining a state of alert in the face of
heavy rains in various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The states of Michoacan, Colima, and Jalisco were most affected
by the tropical storm which destroyed around 250 dwellings.
</P>
<P>
Energy supply and road communication were affected in various
parts of the region and some ports were closed, but re-opened
again Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A military pilot was killed during rescue work in Chinicuila,
Michoacan, when the helicopter crashed Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two people died in a wall collapse in La Minita, Michoacan,
while in Colima a person died when the vehicle in which he was
traveling was carried away by the swelling of the river Los
Mezcales.
</P>
<P>
According to rural authorities, around 500 heads of cattle
perished because of the rains which flooded the municipality of
Cihuatlan, in Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
The National Water Commission said that 11 dams in the state of
Sinaloa in east Mexico are now at full capacity after the flooding
caused by "Greg".
</P>
<P>
In central Mexico, the inundations caused flooding in the
states of Mexico and Morelos, while in the state of Hidalgo, the "
Endho" dam overflowed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain, Norway and Sweden Qualify for Euro 2000 Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Spain, Norway and Sweden
clinched European championship finals berths on Wednesday in the
penultimate round of qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
Spain and the two Scandinavian sides join the Czech Republic
and co-hosts Belgium and the Netherlands in next year's tournament,
leaving 11 places still up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
Perennial qualifiers Spain clinched top spot in group six with
an 8-0 thrashing of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Spain were 5-0 up at halftime and cantered home. Ismael Urzaiz
and Julen Guerrero both scored hat-tricks and Cesar Martin made it
seven and Fernando Hierro completed the rout two minutes from the
end.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen-year old Yossi Benayoun scored a hat-trick as Israel
thrashed San Marino 8-0 in to move into second place and Cyprus
will need to win in Austria to overhaul them even if Israel lose
their last game in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Norway cruised through with a 4-0 home group two win over
Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
A Rudi Istenic own goal got things going after 15 minutes, and
England-based trio Steffen Iversen, Ole Gunnar Solskjaer and
Oyvind Leonhardsen completed matters.
</P>
<P>
Slovenia have the consolation of finishing second after Latvia
could only draw 2-2 at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, who were hosts for the 1992 finals, confirmed their
dominance of group five with a 1-0 win in Luxembourg -- Niclas
Alexandersson getting the only goal after 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Poland need only draw their last game in Sweden to take second
place after drawing 0-0 with England in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
England, who had David Batty sent off after 84 minutes, never
looked like getting the win they needed and now need a Swedish win
over the Poles to finish second.
</P>
<P>
Denmark produced the performance of the night, coming from 2-0
down to beat Italy 3-2 in Naples and guarantee at least a play-off
place.
</P>
<P>
The Danes looked down out after early goals by Diego Fuser and
Christian Vieri.
</P>
<P>
Martin Joergensen pulled one back with a 39th minute penalty
and second half goals by Morten Wieghorst and Jon Dahl Tomasson
secured a famous win. Wieghorst was shown the red card after 81
minutes and Giuliano Giannichedda of Italy was sent off after 88
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Denmark have finished their games and top the group with 14
points, ahead of the Italians on their head-to-head record. Italy
can clinch top spot with a draw in Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, who beat Belarus 2-0, and Wales, cannot now
qualify.
</P>
<P>
Group four remains a bottleneck with Ukraine, France and Russia
battling it out after hard-fought away wins and Iceland still in
with an outside chance.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine stay top on 19 points after a 43rd minute Serhiy Rebrov
penalty gave them a 1-0 victory in Iceland. Russia and France are
a point behind.
</P>
<P>
The world champions came from 1-0 down to beat Armenia 3-2 with
goals from Youri Djorkaeff (penalty), Zinedine Zidane and Lilian
Laslandes.
</P>
<P>
French substitute Frederic Dehu was sent off in the 89th minute,
and Armen Shakgheldyan pulled a goal back with a last-minute
penalty.
</P>
<P>
France have one game left, at home to Iceland, where victory
for the hosts would ensure at least a place in the top two.
</P>
<P>
Russia edged Andorra 2-1 thanks to two goals by Viktor Onopko.
</P>
<P>
They host Ukraine in their last game and a Russian win would
guarantee a top two place and probably top spot.
</P>
<P>
In group eight, Yugoslavia and Ireland both chalked up their
expected victories but the qualification situation is still far
from clearcut.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia returned to the top of the group with an emphatic 4-
2 win over Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Savo Milosevic put the visitors ahead after 10 seconds and
Dejan Stankovic, Ljubinko Drulovic and a Boban Babunski own goal
had virtually settled it before halftime.
</P>
<P>
Ireland made hard work of overcoming Malta 3-2 after goals by
Robbie Keane and Gary Breen had them 2-0 up at halftime.
</P>
<P>
Malat fought back to level terms but Steve Staunton won it for
Ireland with a tremendous 72nd minute free kick.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia now have 16 points to Ireland's 15, with Croatia
third on 14. All three teams have one game left - Ireland against
Macedonia and, in what will be a emotional night in Zagreb,
Croatia against Yugoslavia when the Croats must win to make the
top two.
</P>
<P>
Scotland and Estonia fought out an action-packed goalless draw
in Tallinn to give the Scots the advantage in the race for second
spot in group nine.
</P>
<P>
Group nine winners Czech Republic made it nine wins out of nine
with a 3-0 home success over Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Scots have 12 points from eight games to Estonia's 11 from
nine but with home games against Bosnia and Lithuania to come they
are well-placed to clinch the play-off place.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania edged the Faroes 1-0 and also have 11 points from
nine with Bosnia on eight from eight.
</P>
<P>
Germany took charge of group three with a 4-0 home thrashing of
Northern Ireland, thanks to a first half hat-trick for Christian
Ziege and a second minute strike by Oliver Bierhoff.
</P>
<P>
Germany now have 18 points, two clear of Turkey who needed a
late goal by Tayfur Havatchu to draw 1-1 at Moldova.
</P>
<P>
Germany need only draw their final game against the Turks in
Munich to top the group. Turkey are already guaranteed second.
</P>
<P>
It's a similar situation in group seven where Romania kept
their single point lead over Portugal after the teams drew 1-1 in
Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The Romanians need only win in Liechtenstein to top the group
while Portugal, already sure of second, must beat Hungary and hope
for a Romanian slip.
</P>
<P>
However, Portugal look likely to have the best record of the
nine runners-up and consequently will qualify automatically.
</P>
</TEXT>
