<HEADLINE> Finland, EU Urges Indonesia to Co-operate With UN on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tarja Halonen, Finnish
Foreign Minister and rotating chairman of the council of European
Union (EU), Wednesday urged Indonesia to co-operate with the
United Nations on East Timor.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Halonen said that shocking news
from East Timor tells that the violence there is escalating into
total chaos while the last elements of foreign presence in this
territory are being forced out as U.N. Assessment Mission on East
Timor (UNAMET) will start leaving tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Halonen added that the EU has delivered a message of great
concern to Ali Alatas, Foreign Minister of Indonesia. "We urged
Indonesia to turn to the UN Security Council and requested it to
authorize an international armed presence to assist Indonesia in
this task."
</P>
<P>
"We all share the same sense of urgency and gravity of the
situation. The Security Council will shortly be convened at an
emergency meeting to address the East Timor crisis," the Finnish
Foreign Minister said. 
</P>
