<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeastern China Spending More on Nature Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The government of Jilin
Province in northeastern China recently allocated two million yuan
(240,000 U.S. dollars) to expand protection of the Xianghai Swamp
Nature Reserve.
</P>
<P>
Concerned by severe drought conditions in the reserve in July,
Provincial Governor Hong Hu decided to channel more water into the
area, saying the rare animal species should be protected.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is located in Tongyu County in the western part of
the province, where the Inner Mongolian Plateau intersects with
the Northeast China Plain, and right in the flight path of
migratory fowl.
</P>
<P>
It covers more than 100,000 hectares and is home to 253 species
of birds, including red-crowned and white cranes, white storks,
and gold and gray vultures. The site was designated as a national
reserve in 1986 and a nature reserve by the United Nations
Wildlife Fund in 1992.
</P>
<P>
However, a four-year dry period has posed a considerable threat
to the survival of the waterfowl.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
