<HEADLINE> Blair, Clinton Agree on East Timor Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and the U.S. President Bill Clinton agreed Wednesday to
support efforts to get an international force to East Timor if the
United Nations and Indonesia agreed, British officials said.
</P>
<P>
Blair and Clinton discussed the East Timor situation in a
20-minute phone call, a Reuters report quoted a spokesman for
Blair as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They agreed the importance of supporting efforts to get an
international U.N. force" to East Timor subject to approval by the
U.N. Security Council and the Indonesian government, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Britain announced that one of its warship, the HMS
Glasgow, which is currently in the South China Sea, was preparing
to head for the waters around East Timor to support any U.N.
peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
Britain is also sending around a dozen military planners to the
region to work under an Australian command. 
</P>
</TEXT>
