<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tech, Financial Firms Collaborating to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- An alliance of U.S. major
computer and Internet firms Wednesday released a universal format
that it hopes to make it easier and more appealing for consumers
and businesses to pay for goods and services over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The format, known as Electronic Commerce Modeling Language
(ECML), uses a set of uniform field names that streamlines the
process by which merchants collect electronic data for shipping,
billing and payment.
</P>
<P>
According to the consortium which includes American Online,
IBM, Microsoft, Compaq, American Express, Visa and other blue-chip
companies, merchants today are conducting business on the Internet
using HTML-based forms. The data format used in these forms varies
from one merchant to another. End-users find the diversity
confusing and the process of manually filling in these forms to be
tedious.
</P>
<P>
Software tools called digital wallets can help this situation
by making the shopping experience easier for consumers. A digital
wallet is an application or service that assists consumers in
conducting online transactions by allowing them to store billing,
shipping and payment information, and to use this information to
automatically complete a merchant's check-out page. This greatly
simplifies the check-out process and minimizes the need for a
consumer to manually complete a merchant's form every time.
</P>
<P>
Digital wallets have been successfully built into browsers, but
the proliferation of digital wallets has been hampered by the lack
of standard.
</P>
<P>
Most Internet merchants use a variety of nonstandard forms. As
a result, most consumers have to enter their name, address, credit
card number and expiration date at every site each time they want
to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
According to research firm Jupiter Communications, 27 percent
of consumers have abandoned items at the checkout line at a Web
storefront because they found filling out forms too tedious a
task.
</P>
<P>
Now ECML provides a simple set of guidelines for Web merchants
that will enbale digital wallets from multiple vendors to automate
the exchange of information between users and merchants.
</P>
<P>
ECML also can be used with existing data privacy and security
methods, according to the consortium. Online merchants can
implement ECML without a license. The alliance said that ECML is
the first in what will be a series of e-commerce standard
initiatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Not to Take Unilateral Move in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada will not move
unilaterally into the current conflict of East Timor, Prime
Minister Jean Chretien said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to move in a multilateral way. I don't think that
Canada can move with troops in East Timor," he told reporters
after announcing the appointment of Adrienne Clarkson as governor
general in the foyer of the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
Chretien made the remarks a day before leaving for New Zealand
for the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit, where some
countries are likely to press Indonesia to allow peacekeepers into
East Timor, according to Canadian media reports.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian army declared a state of emergency in East Timor
Tuesday morning amid serious violence sparked after the
announcement of the direct autonomy ballot on September 4.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Defense Minister Wiranto has reiterated that the
Indonesian government can get its own security forces to restore
law and order in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Canada sent a team of observers at the end of last month for
the planned ballot. The country has also claimed to be "the third
largest donor to East Timor," providing more than 4 million
Canadian dollars (about 2.7 million U.S. dollars) this year to the
former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
