<DOCNO> XIE19990909.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forecast on Italy's Economy Upped By Employers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Confindustria, the Italian
employers' association, Wednesday upped its forecasts for economic
growth in 1999 and 2000, confirming signs of a rally in the second
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Confindustria said it expected the 1999 GDP to rise 1.1 percent
and next year's by 2.2 percent. These figures compared to 0.9
percent and 1.9 percent in forecasts released last June.
</P>
<P>
"The gap that has existed for most of this decade between
Italian and European growth rates seems to be closing," the
organization's study center said.
</P>
<P>
Last year Italy had the European Union's lowest growth rate,
some 1.5 percent below the EU average. Confindustria said the
difference was likely to fall to 0.8 percent this year and 0.5
percent in the following two years.
</P>
<P>
Driving the mini-recovery were exports which were bouncing back
from the dive at the end of 1998 and also investments which were
expanding thanks to government incentives.
</P>
<P>
"But the gap with Europe has not yet been closed," employers
said. To do this lower taxes and freer markets were necessary,
along with a streamlined public administration and more modern
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government's most recent forecast for growth this
year was 1.3 percent, which would still put Italy at the bottom of
the European pile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
